{"title_page": "Iranian Space Agency", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox space agency\n| name          = Iranian Space Agency<br />(ISA)\n| acronym       = ISA\n| image         = Iranian Space Agency logo.png\n| size          = 150px\n| caption       = Official logo of ISA\n\n| spaceport     = [[Imam Khomeini Spaceport]]\n| established   = {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|mf=no|2004|2|1}}\n| owner         = [[Ministry of Information and Communications Technology (Iran)|Ministry of Communications and Information Technology]], Iran\n| headquarters  = [[Tehran]], [[Mahdasht]], [[Shahrud]], [[Qom]]\n| budget        = $4.6 million (FY 2017)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://financialtribune.com/articles/sci-tech/55397/cuts-and-extensions-in-irans-ict-201718-budget|title=Cuts and Extensions in Iran's ICT 2017/18 Budget|date=14 December 2016|work=Financial Tribune|accessdate=11 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220150555/https://financialtribune.com/articles/sci-tech/55397/cuts-and-extensions-in-irans-ict-201718-budget|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| administrator = [[Morteza Barari]]\n| URL           = {{URL|www.isa.ir}}\n}}\n{{Spaceflight sidebar}}\n\nThe '''Iranian Space Agency''' ('''ISA''', [[Persian language|Persian]]: {{lang|fa|\u0633\u0627\u0632\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0641\u0636\u0627\u06cc\u06cc \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646}} ''S\u0101zm\u0101ne Faz\u0101iye Ir\u0101n'') is [[Iran]]'s [[Government of Iran|governmental]] [[space agency]].\nIran became an [[Timeline of first orbital launches by country|orbital-launch-capable nation]] in 2009.<ref name=ptv20120203/> Iran is one of the 24 founding members of the [[United Nations Committee on the Peaceful Uses of Outer Space]] (COPUOS), which was set up on 13 December 1958.<ref name=ptv20120203>{{cite web|url=http://presstv.com/detail/224597.html|title=Iran to establish national satellite launch base |publisher=Press TV|date=3 February 2012|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303230604/http://presstv.com/detail/224597.html|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nISA was established on 28 February 2004, according to the Article 9 of the Law for Tasks and Authorizations of the [[Ministry of Information and Communications Technology of Iran|Ministry of Communications and Information Technology]] passed on 10 December 2003 by the [[Parliament of Iran]]. Based on the approved statute ISA mandated to cover and support all the activities in Iran concerning the peaceful applications of space science and technology under the leadership of a Supreme Council of Space chaired by the [[President of Iran]].\n\nThe Council's main goals included policy making for the application of space technologies aiming peaceful uses of outer space, manufacturing, launching and use of the national research satellites, approving the space related state and private sector programs, promoting the partnership of the private and cooperative sectors in efficient uses of space, identifying guidelines concerning the regional and international cooperation in space issues.\n\nTo follow and implement the strategies set by the Council, ISA affiliated with the [[Ministry of Information and Communications Technology of Iran|Ministry of Communication and Information Technology]] in the form of an autonomous organization, was organized. The president of ISA held the position of the Vice-Minister of Communications and Information Technology and the secretariat of Supreme Council of Space at the same time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://parviztarikhi.wordpress.com/features-2/more-significant-role-for-iran%e2%80%99s-space-administration|title=More significant role for Iran\u2019s space administration|publisher=Parviz Tarikhi|date=11 November 2010|accessdate=17 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718103724/http://parviztarikhi.wordpress.com/features-2/more-significant-role-for-iran%e2%80%99s-space-administration/ |archive-date=18 July 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSince 2015, Iran's space program has been quietly suspended by [[President Rouhani]] following international pressures.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://warisboring.com/iran-just-cancelled-its-space-program-5b1d5ce50bd6|title=Archived copy|accessdate=24 September 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925012918/https://warisboring.com/iran-just-cancelled-its-space-program-5b1d5ce50bd6 |archivedate=25 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Budget ==\n{{See also|Politics of Iran#Budget}}\n\nThe proposed budget for the Iranian year [[Iranian calendars|1393]] (2014\u20132015) is 1,865,583 million rials (US$71,753,192). Other related organizations have received separate budget allocations. [[Iranian Space Research Center]] has received an additional 1,751,000 million rials (US$67,346,100) of budget for the year 1393.<ref>{{cite book|title=Budget Bill of 1393 (\u0644\u0627\u064a\u062d\u0647 \u0628\u0648\u062f\u062c\u0647 \u0633\u0627\u0644 1393 \u0643\u0644 \u0643\u0634\u0648\u0631)|publisher=Secretariat of Planning and Supervision, Office of President|date=December 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe budget for the year 2008 was mentioned to be US$3.9 billion (2008).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aftab.ir/news/view/2008/feb/20/c2c1203499802_economy_marketing_business_information_technology_mobile.php |title=\u0627\u062e\u062a\u0635\u0627\u0635 \u06f3 \u0647\u0632\u0627\u0631 \u0648 \u06f9\u06f6\u06f0 \u0645\u06cc\u0644\u06cc\u0627\u0631\u062f \u062a\u0648\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u0631\u0627\u06cc \u0633\u0627\u0632\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0641\u0636\u0627\u06cc\u06cc \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646|agency=[[Aftab News Agency]]|date=February 2008|accessdate=17 January 2011}}</ref> However it was not apparent whether the allocation was just for one year or a longer period.\n\nUnder president [[Hassan Rouhani]], the proposed 2017-budget for the Iranian Space Agency fell to a low of US$4.6 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://financialtribune.com/articles/sci-tech/55397/cuts-and-extensions-in-irans-ict-201718-budget|title=Archived copy|accessdate=14 December 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220150555/https://financialtribune.com/articles/sci-tech/55397/cuts-and-extensions-in-irans-ict-201718-budget|archivedate=20 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Satellite launch vehicle (SLV) ==\n{{Main|Safir (rocket)|Simorgh (rocket)}}\n[[File:Noor_satellite.jpg|thumb|Noor satellite launch]]\n\n=== Safir SLV ===\nIran has developed an expendable satellite launch vehicle named [[Safir (rocket)|Safir SLV]]. Measuring 22 m in height with a core diameter of 1.25 m, with two liquid propellant stages, a single thrust chambered first stage and a two-thrust chambered, step-throttled second stage, the SLV has a lift off mass exceeding 26 tons. The first stage consists of a lengthened up-rated [[Shahab-3C]]. According to the technical documentation presented in the annual meeting of the [[United Nations Office for Outer Space Affairs]], it is a two-stage rocket with all liquid propellant engines. The first stage is capable of carrying the payload to the maximum altitude of 68 kilometers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oosa.unvienna.org/pdf/pres/stsc2009/tech-15.pdf|title=Archived copy|accessdate=15 March 2009|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905233838/http://www.oosa.unvienna.org/pdf/pres/stsc2009/tech-15.pdf|archivedate=5 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== Safir-1B ====\nThe Safir-1B is the second generation of Safir SLV and can carry a satellite weighing 60 kg into an [[Elliptic orbit|elliptical orbit]] of 300 to 450 km. The thrust of the Safir-1B rocket engine has been increased from 32 to 37 tons.\n\n=== Simorgh SLV ===\nIn 2010, a more powerful rocket named [[Simorgh (rocket)|Simorgh]] (Phoenix) was built. Its mission is to carry heavier satellites into orbit.<ref name=\"payvand1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.payvand.com/news/10/feb/1025.html|title=Iran unveils three new home-made satellites|publisher=Payvand.com|date=22 November 2006|accessdate=6 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100206215559/http://www.payvand.com/news/10/feb/1025.html|archive-date=6 February 2010|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tehrantimes.com/index_View.asp?code=213671|title=Iran launches spacecraft carrying animals / Space program breakthroughs signal the dawn of a new era of national development: Ahmadinejad|work=Tehran Times|accessdate=6 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100212225529/http://www.tehrantimes.com/index_View.asp?code=213671|archive-date=12 February 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> The Simorgh rocket is 27 meters (89 ft) long, and has a mass of 77 tonnes (85 tons).[4] Its first stage is powered by four main engines, each generating up to 29,000 kilograms (64,000 lb) of thrust, plus a fifth which will be used for [[attitude control]], which provides an additional 13,600 kilograms (30,000 lb). At liftoff, these engines will generate a total of 130,000 kilograms (290,000 lb) of thrust. Simorgh is capable of putting a 350-kilogram (770 lb) payload into a 500-kilometer (310 mi) low Earth orbit. In 2015, Israeli media reported the missile is capable of taking a manned spacecraft or satellite into space.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/israeli-tv-shows-iranian-missile-that-can-reach-far-beyond-europe/|title=Archived copy|accessdate=29 January 2015|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161225030054/http://www.timesofisrael.com/israeli-tv-shows-iranian-missile-that-can-reach-far-beyond-europe//|archivedate=25 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jerusalemonline.com/news/world-news/around-the-globe/is-iran-on-its-way-to-sending-a-man-to-outer-space-9360|title=Archived copy|accessdate=29 January 2015|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701192725/http://www.jerusalemonline.com/news/world-news/around-the-globe/is-iran-on-its-way-to-sending-a-man-to-outer-space-9360|archivedate=1 July 2015}}</ref> The first flight of the Simorgh rocket occurred on 19 April 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://defense-update.com/20160424_simorgh.html|title=Simorgh First Launch \u2013 an Iranian Success or Failure? {{!}} Defense Update:|last=Eshel|first=Tamir|website=defense-update.com|access-date=29 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161127192324/http://defense-update.com/20160424_simorgh.html|archive-date=27 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Qoqnoos SLV ===\nOn 2 February 2013, the head of the [[Iranian Space Agency]], Hamid Fazeli mentioned that the new satellite launch vehicle, Qoqnoos will be used after the Simorgh SLV for heavier payloads.<ref name=\"mehrnews1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mehrnews.com/fa/NewsDetail.aspx?NewsID=1805674|title=Details and revealing of Nahid Satellite, Launch of Nahid with Safir B-1 (Persian)|publisher=mehrnews.com|date=2 February 2013 |accessdate=3 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130205042658/http://www.mehrnews.com/fa/newsdetail.aspx?NewsID=1805674|archive-date=5 February 2013|url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"mehrnews2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mehrnews.com/en/NewsDetail.aspx?NewsID=1806425|title=Ahmadinejad to unveil Nahid Satellite soon (English)|publisher=mehrnews.com|date=2 February 2013|accessdate=3 February 2013}}{{dead link|date=November 2017|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref>\n\n== Sub-orbital launches ==\n{{See also|Science and technology in Iran}}\n\nOn 25 February 2007, the Iranian state-run television announced that a rocket, created by the ministries of science and defense and which carried an unspecified cargo, was successfully launched. This could have been the maiden test flight of the three staged [[Safir (rocket)|Safir SLV]] which ended in a failure. Later on it was noted by Iranian President [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] that the failure was due to a technical problem in the last stage of the rocket.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rDKanxOGXWk&NR=1|title=President Mahmoud Ahmadinejad \u2013 Campaign Documentary (2/4)|via=YouTube|date=31 May 2009 |accessdate=6 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140623004824/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rDKanxOGXWk&NR=1|archive-date=23 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 February 2008, Iran successfully launched a two-stage all solid-fuel sub-orbital sounding rocket [[Kavoshgar-1]] (Explorer-1), for a maiden sub-orbital test flight from [[Shahroud]], its newly inaugurated domestic space launch complex.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/7225699.stm|title=Iranians inaugurate space project|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=4 February 2008|access-date=4 February 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080209143738/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/7225699.stm|archive-date=9 February 2008|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail.aspx?id=41636&sectionid=351020101|title=Iran's Kavoshgar1 lifts off for space|publisher=[[Press TV]]|date=4 February 2008|access-date=4 February 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208120433/http://www.presstv.ir/detail.aspx?id=41636&sectionid=351020101|archive-date=8 December 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>\nThe first stage of the rocket detached after 90 seconds and returned to Earth with the help of a parachute while the second stage reached a 200 km altitude before reentering the Earth's atmosphere after 300 seconds. The third section of the rocket, containing an atmospheric probe, climbed to 250 km while successfully transmitting scientific data on the atmosphere and the electromagnetic waves on its path back to Earth. It deployed a parachute after six minutes at a lower altitude.\n\nThe second Kavoshgar ([[Kavoshgar-2]]), which carried a space-lab and a restoration system, was launched in November 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.farsnews.net/newstext.php?nn=8709061266|title=Fars News Agency : \u0627\u064a\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u0645\u0648\u0634\u0643 \u0643\u0627\u0648\u0634\u06af\u0631 2 \u0631\u0627 \u0628\u0627 \u0645\u0648\u0641\u0642\u064a\u062a \u0628\u0647 \u0641\u0636\u0627 \u067e\u0631\u062a\u0627\u0628 \u0643\u0631\u062f|publisher=Farsnews.net|accessdate=6 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723130155/http://www.farsnews.net/newstext.php?nn=8709061266 |archive-date=23 July 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Animals in space ===\n{{See also|Monkeys in space}}\n\n* On 3 February 2010, ISA launched a [[Kavoshgar-3]] (Explorer-3) rocket with one rodent, two turtles, and several worms into sub-orbital space and returned them to Earth alive. The rocket was enabled to transfer electronic data and live footage back to Earth. The Iranian Aerospace Organization (IAO) showed live video transmission of mini-environmental lab to enable further studies on the biological capsule.<ref name=\"Iran Fires Satellite Carrier into Space\">{{cite news|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/10/feb/1026.html|title=Iran Fires Satellite Carrier into Space|date=2 February 2010|publisher=payvand.com |accessdate=5 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100208185122/http://www.payvand.com/news/10/feb/1026.html|archive-date=8 February 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> This was the first [[Animals in space|biological]] [[Payload (air and space craft)|payload]] launched by Iran.<ref name=mcuk20100204>{{cite web|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/news/world/811677-animals-are-fired-into-space-in-iranian-rocket |title=Animals are fired into space in Iranian rocket|work=Metro|location=UK|date=4 February 2010|access-date=5 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100413085349/http://www.metro.co.uk/news/world/811677-animals-are-fired-into-space-in-iranian-rocket|archive-date=13 April 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> Iran is the sixth country to send [[animals in space]].\n\n* On 15 March 2011, the ISA launched the [[Kavoshgar-4]] (Explorer-4) rocket carrying a test capsule designed to carry a monkey but without living creatures on board.\n\n* [[Kavoshgar-5]] (Explorer-5) carrying a live monkey was launched for a 20-minute sub-orbital flight in September 2011, however the mission failed. On 3 October 2011, Iran indefinitely postponed further plans while scientists reviewed readiness for future missions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/272624/irans-monkey-does-not-make-it-to-space/|title=Iran's monkey does not make it to space |agency=Agence France-Presse|newspaper=The Express Tribune|date=12 October 2011|accessdate=20 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305042806/http://tribune.com.pk/story/272624/irans-monkey-does-not-make-it-to-space/|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2012, Iran announced that it would send more living creatures into the space by the summer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.farsnews.com/newstext.php?nn%3D9102110289|title=Archived copy|accessdate=4 May 2012|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503105702/http://english.farsnews.com/newstext.php?nn=9102110289|archivedate=3 May 2012}}</ref> Following the last failed attempt, ISA was seeking to successfully send a monkey into space by 2013.<ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/science/2013/01/16/iran-launching-monkey-into-space/ Iran launching monkey into space] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702023236/http://www.foxnews.com/science/2013/01/16/iran-launching-monkey-into-space/|date=2 July 2015}}</ref> ISA head Hamid Fazeli told the Iranian news agency Mehr that the designated monkeys are currently in quarantine.<ref>[http://www.timesofisrael.com/iran-to-launch-a-monkey-into-space/ Times of Israel. Iran to Launch a Monkey into Space] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304060710/http://www.timesofisrael.com/iran-to-launch-a-monkey-into-space/|date=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n* On 29 January 2013, Iranian state media announced that a monkey was sent into space and returned safely aboard the [[Pishgam]] capsule, after having reached a height of 120 km.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dareini |first=Ali|title=Iran Says It Sent Monkey into Space and Back|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/iran-monkey-successfully-space-18333221|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=28 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130131005807/http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/iran-monkey-successfully-space-18333221|archive-date=31 January 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> This was the first time that Iran has sent a [[primate]] into space, 54 years after the first monkeys [[Able and Baker]] returned safely. No details on the timing or location of the launch were given.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.3news.co.nz/Iran-sends-monkey-into-space/tabid/1216/articleID/284734/Default.aspx|work=3 News NZ|title=Iran sends monkey into space|date=29 January 2013|access-date=29 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130213094454/http://www.3news.co.nz/Iran-sends-monkey-into-space/tabid/1216/articleID/284734/Default.aspx|archive-date=13 February 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n* On 14 December 2013, Iran launched a second monkey, named [[Fargam]], on a suborbital flight.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irna.ir/en/News/80950169/Art_&_Culture/Second_monkey_sent_into_space|title=Archived copy|accessdate=11 August 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304103726/http://www.irna.ir/en/News/80950169/Art_%26_Culture/Second_monkey_sent_into_space|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref> The monkey is reported to have been retrieved successfully and safe, after the short 15-minute flight.\n\n== Orbital launches ==\n{{See also|List of orbital launch systems}}\n[[File:Zafar_Satellite.jpg|thumb|Zafar Satellite.]]\n\nOn 17 August 2008, Iran proceeded with the second test launch of a two-stage [[Safir (rocket)|Safir]] SLV from a site south of [[Semnan, Iran|Semnan city]] in the northern part of the [[Dasht-e Kavir|Dasht-e-Kavir desert]]. Reza Taghizadeh, head of the Iranian Aerospace Organization, told state television \"The Safir (Ambassador) satellite carrier was launched today and, for the first time, we successfully launched a dummy satellite into orbit\".\n\nOn 2 February 2009, Iranian state television reported that Iran's first domestically made satellite [[Omid (satellite)|Omid]] ({{lang-fa|\u0627\u0645\u06cc\u062f}}, meaning \"Hope\") had been successfully launched into [[Low Earth orbit]] by a version of Iran's Safir rocket, the [[Safir (rocket)|Safir-2]] and therefore Iran became the 9th country to put a [[Omid (satellite)|domestically built satellite]] into orbit.<ref name=Reuters>{{cite news|title=Iran launches first home-made satellite: state TV|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idUSTRE5120NN20090203|agency=Reuters|date=3 February 2009|accessdate=3 February 2009 |author=Fredrik Dahl and Edmund Blair|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090204204419/http://www.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idUSTRE5120NN20090203|archive-date=4 February 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> The operation was made to coincide with the 30th anniversary of the [[Iranian Revolution]].\n\nIn February 2011, Iranian president [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] announced that there will be many launches of indigenously produced orbiters in 2011\u20132012 period.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gsn.nti.org/gsn/nw_20110207_8612.php|title=Iran Plans Multiple Satellite Launches &#124; NTI|publisher=Gsn.nti.org|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007102011/http://gsn.nti.org/gsn/nw_20110207_8612.php|archive-date=7 October 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIran plans to send one-ton satellites into an orbit of 1000 km and is setting up a new [[Spaceport|launch base]] for this purpose. Iran is also planning to launch satellites into orbits of up to [[Geosynchronous orbit|36,000 km]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://presstv.com/detail/230008.html|title=Archived copy|accessdate=19 March 2012|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303231603/http://presstv.com/detail/230008.html|archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/12/feb/1110.html|title=Archived copy |accessdate=11 February 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140225065920/http://www.payvand.com/news/12/feb/1110.html|archivedate=25 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://presstv.com/detail/225942.html|title=Archived copy|accessdate=11 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303222208/http://presstv.com/detail/225942.html |archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Launched satellites ==\n{{See also|Communications in Iran}}\n\n[[File:Omid 0665.jpg|thumb|[[Omid satellite]]]]\n[[Iran]] is the [[Timeline of first orbital launches by country#List of first orbital launches by country|9th country to put a domestically-built satellite into orbit using its own launcher]] and the sixth to send [[animals in space]].]]\n\n* On 28 October 2005, a [[Kosmos-3M]] booster rocket launched [[Sina-1]]. The joint Iranian Russian Sina-1 project cost US$15 million, and the launch made Iran the 43rd country to possess its own satellite.<ref>{{cite web|last=Alam|first=Ameer|url=http://www.pakalumni.com/profiles/blogs/1119293:BlogPost:64819|title=The Emerging Iranian Space Program \u2013 PakAlumni Worldwide: The Global Social Network |publisher=Pakalumni.com|date=12 April 2009|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316094708/http://www.pakalumni.com/profiles/blogs/1119293:BlogPost:64819|archive-date=16 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n* [[Huanjing (satellite)|Environment 1]], a joint research satellite of [[Iran]], [[China]] and [[Thailand]] was launched on a Chinese [[Long March 2C]] carrier rocket on 6 September 2008, aimed at boosting cooperation on [[natural disaster]]s such as [[flooding]], [[drought]], [[typhoon]], [[landslide]] and [[earthquake]]. The twin [[Earth observation satellite]]s of eight planned were launched from [[Taiyuan Satellite Launch Center|Taiyuan SLC]]. The satellites will work as a constellation with six other satellites yet to be launched. Its observational footprint is 720 km. With a lifespan of more than three years, they have state-of-the-art imaging systems and infrared cameras and provide a global scan every two days. Iran had shouldered US$6.5 million out of the $44 million of the total project cost.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://scitech.people.com.cn/GB/7836524.html|title=\"\u73af\u5883\u51cf\u707e\"A\u3001B\u536b\u661f\u4e00\u7bad\u53cc\u661f\u53d1\u5c04\u6210\u529f|publisher=\u4eba\u6c11\u7f51|date=6 September 2008|accessdate=6 September 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207043054/http://scitech.people.com.cn/GB/7836524.html|archive-date=7 February 2009|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"spacedaily.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.spacedaily.com/news/iran-05d.html|title=Iran, Russia Sign 'Zohreh' Satellite Deal|publisher=Spacedaily.com|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205104231/http://www.spacedaily.com/news/iran-05d.html|archive-date=5 February 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n* [[Omid (satellite)|Omid]], Iran's second satellite, was placed in orbit in February 2009, and was described as a data-processing satellite for research and telecommunications.<ref name=Reuters /><ref>{{cite web|title=Iran puts Omid data-processing satellite into orbit|publisher=[[IRNA]]|url=http://www5.irna.ir/En/View/FullStory/?NewsId=335409&IdLanguage=3|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090206161943/http://www5.irna.ir/En/View/FullStory/?NewsId=335409&IdLanguage=3|url-status=dead|archive-date=6 February 2009|date=3 February 2009|accessdate=3 February 2009}}</ref>\n\n* [[Rasad Satellite|Rasad-1]] is an imaging satellite that has been built and launched successfully by Iran. The satellite was sent into the 260 kilometres orbit by a Safir rocket launcher on 15 June 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sayfa Bulunamad\u0131|language=Turkish|url=http://www.islamidavet.com/english/2010/08/25/iran-to-launch-rasad-1-satellite-in-2011/|accessdate=25 March 2011}}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref name=\"globalsecurity.org\">{{cite web|author=John Pike|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/space/world/iran/irans-second-satellite-launch.htm|title=Iran's Second Satellite Launch |publisher=Globalsecurity.org|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106232622/http://www.globalsecurity.org/space/world/iran/irans-second-satellite-launch.htm|archive-date=6 January 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Hello, Guest|url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/2011/jun/15/iran-launches-homemade-satellite-into-orbit/|title=Iran launches homemade satellite into orbit &#124; UTSanDiego.com|publisher=Signonsandiego.com|date=15 June 2011|accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref> It beams back to earth pictures with 150-meter resolution. It [[orbital decay|decayed from orbit]] three weeks after launch, on 6 July 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zarya.info/Diaries/2011.php|title=2011|work=Zarya Diaries|first=Robert|last=Christy|accessdate=12 July 2011|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019065644/http://www.zarya.info/Diaries/2011.php|archivedate=19 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planet4589.org/space/jsr/latest.html |title=planet4589|work=Jonathan's space Report|first=Jonathan|last=Mcdowell|accessdate=16 July 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718073237/http://planet4589.org/space/jsr/latest.html|archive-date=18 July 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n* [[Navid (satellite)|Navid-e Elm-o Sanat]] (also known as 'Ya Mahdi') which is an \"experimental satellite\" built by students for testing camera and telecommunications equipment was revealed to the public on 3 February 2010. It has store-dump capability and a resolution of 400 meters. On 3 February 2012, Iranian press reported that Iran has successfully launched its domestically-built Navid-e Elm-o Sanat satellite into orbit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail/224596.html|title=PressTV \u2013 Iran successfully launches new satellite into orbit|publisher=Press TV|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205212904/http://www.presstv.ir/detail/224596.html|archive-date=5 February 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The satellite remained in orbit for two months, before [[atmospheric reentry|reentering the atmosphere]] on 1 April 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reentrynews.aero.org/2012005A.html|title=Navis Satellite|work=Recent Reentries|publisher=Center for Orbital and Reentry Debris Studies|accessdate=20 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504010357/http://reentrynews.aero.org/2012005A.html|archive-date=4 May 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n* [[Fajr (satellite)|Fajr]], is an imaging satellite which also carries an experimental locally made GPS system built by [[Iran Electronics Industries]]. The satellite had a life span of 1.5 years and an imaging resolution of 500 meters. It is the first Iranian satellite to use \"cold gas thruster\" and has solar pannels. Originally, it was to be launched in 2012. As were alleged, non-announced by Iran one failed launches of Fajr satellites occurred on 23 May in 2012.<ref name=\"Fajr_failure?\">{{cite journal|last=Hansen|first=Nick|title=Rocket science \u2013 Iran's rocket programme|journal=Jane's Intelligence Review |date=1 October 2012|volume=24|issue=10}}</ref> Finally, Fajr was successfully launched and placed into orbit on 2 February 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.com/Detail/2015/02/02/395807/Iran-places-satellite-into-orbit|title=Archived copy|accessdate=2 February 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160228192939/http://presstv.com/Detail/2015/02/02/395807/Iran-places-satellite-into-orbit|archivedate=28 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxbusiness.com/technology/2015/02/02/state-television-reports-iran-launches-satellite-called-fajr-into-space-amid/|title=Archived copy |accessdate=12 June 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927061418/http://www.foxbusiness.com/technology/2015/02/02/state-television-reports-iran-launches-satellite-called-fajr-into-space-amid/|archivedate=27 September 2015}}</ref> On 26 February 2015, Fajr [[Atmospheric entry|reentered]] earth's atmosphere after 23.8 days in orbit.<ref name=\"Gunter\">{{cite web |url=http://space.skyrocket.de/doc_sdat/fajr.htm|title=Fajr|first=Gunter|last=Krebs|work=Gunter's Space Page|accessdate=27 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212013941/http://space.skyrocket.de/doc_sdat/fajr.htm|archive-date=12 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n* [[Dousti (satellite)|Dousti]], satellite designed for Earth observation. Launched by a Safir rocket in 5 February 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://space.skyrocket.de/doc_sdat/dousti.htm|title=Archived copy |access-date=8 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209180108/https://space.skyrocket.de/doc_sdat/dousti.htm|archive-date=9 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The launch failed.\n\n* [[AUT-SAT]], is a [[Microsatellite (spaceflight)|microsatellite]] being developed by students of [[Amirkabir University of Technology]]. It is designed as a remote sensing satellite with store-dump capability. It was launched on 15 January 2019 by a Simorgh rocket, but failed to reach orbit.<ref name=\"tebyan.net\"/><ref name=\"ayenehnashriat.com\"/> Amir Kabir satellite, weighing 80 kg, will reportedly be placed in a sun-synchronous orbit of 660 km in radius, and will remain in space between three and five years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.com/detail/2012/07/22/252215/iran-aims-to-launch-another-satellite/|title=Archived copy|accessdate=24 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303210527/http://www.presstv.com/detail/2012/07/22/252215/iran-aims-to-launch-another-satellite/|archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref> The launcher is expected to be a Simorgh missile.<ref name=\"english.farsnews.com\"/>\n\n* On 9 February 2020, Iran successfully launched the [[communication satellite]], Zafar 1, through a [[Simorgh (rocket)|Simorgh]] rocket from [[Imam Khomeini Spaceport|Imam Khomeini Space Center]] at 19:15 local time. However, spokesman for the [[Ministry of Defence and Armed Forces Logistics (Iran)|defence ministry]]'s space programme, Ahmad Hosseini, notified that the satellite didn't reach the required speed in its final moments for being put in the [[orbit]].<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.spacewar.com/reports/Iran_satellite_launch_fails_in_blow_to_space_programme_999.html|title=Iran satellite launch fails, in blow to space program|accessdate=9 February 2020|website=Space War}}</ref>\n\n* On 22 April 2020, Iran successfully launched \"Noor\" (Farsi for \"Light\"), a military satellite, into a 426 x 444 km sun-synchronous orbit.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.space.com/iran-launches-first-military-satellite.html|title=Iran launches its 1st military satellite into orbit: reports|accessdate=22 April 2020|website=Space.com}}</ref>\n\n== Unlaunched satellites ==\n* [[Nahid (satellite)|Nahid]] (1), satellite with folding solar panels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.farsnews.com/newstext.php?nn%3D13910213000402|title=Archived copy|accessdate=15 May 2012|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304002859/http://www.farsnews.com/newstext.php?nn=13910213000402|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/news/313410-Russia-Iran-space-cooperation/|title=Archived copy|accessdate=1 December 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201080642/https://www.rt.com/news/313410-Russia-Iran-space-cooperation/ |archivedate=1 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n* [[Toloo (satellite)|Toloo]], is the first of a new generation of [[reconnaissance satellite]]s being built by [[Iran Electronics Industries]] with [[SIGINT]] capabilities.<ref name=\"payvand.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/11/nov/1025.html|title=Iran to Launch Toloo Satellite Next Year|publisher=Payvand.com|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111217073304/http://www.payvand.com/news/11/nov/1025.html|archive-date=17 December 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> It will be launched by a [[Simorgh]].<ref name=\"english.farsnews.com\">{{cite web|url=http://english.farsnews.com/newstext.aspx?nn%3D13931113001060|title=Archived copy|accessdate=3 February 2015|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150709031827/http://english.farsnews.com/newstext.aspx?nn=13931113001060|archivedate=9 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n* [[Nasir 1 (satellite)|Nasir 1]], Iran's indigenously designed [[satellite navigation system]] (SAT NAV) has been manufactured to find the precise locations of satellites moving in orbit.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/middle-east/report-iran-unveils-self-made-satellite-navigation-system-1.433673|title=Archived copy|accessdate=3 June 2012|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716041438/http://www.haaretz.com/news/middle-east/report-iran-unveils-self-made-satellite-navigation-system-1.433673|archivedate=16 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.payvand.com/news/12/may/1309.html|title=Archived copy|accessdate=19 January 2013|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618140138/http://www.payvand.com/news/12/may/1309.html|archivedate=18 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n* [[Sharif (satellite)|Sharif]] satellite was originally scheduled for launch in 2012 is an observation satellite with an imaging resolution of better than 12.5 meters. The satellite is manufactured by [[Sharif University of Technology]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://isna.ir/fa/news/91021307234/%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%8A%D8%B3-%D8%B3%D8%A7%D8%B2%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%86-%D9%81%D8%B6%D8%A7%D9%8A%D9%8A-%D8%AE%D8%A8%D8%B1-%D8%AF%D8%A7%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D8%B9%D8%B2%D8%A7%D9%85-%D9%85%D9%88%D8%AC%D9%88%D8%AF-%D8%B2%D9%86%D8%AF%D9%87|title=Archived copy|accessdate=15 May 2012|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304111829/http://isna.ir/fa/news/91021307234/%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%8A%D8%B3-%D8%B3%D8%A7%D8%B2%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%86-%D9%81%D8%B6%D8%A7%D9%8A%D9%8A-%D8%AE%D8%A8%D8%B1-%D8%AF%D8%A7%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D8%B9%D8%B2%D8%A7%D9%85-%D9%85%D9%88%D8%AC%D9%88%D8%AF-%D8%B2%D9%86%D8%AF%D9%87|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n* [[Zafar-1]], is an imaging satellite to be launched in 2012 and will have a resolution better than 80 meters.<ref name=\"tebyan.net\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tebyan.net/index.aspx?pid=17257&threadID=280555 |title=\u0631\u0648\u0646\u0645\u0627\u06cc\u06cc \u0627\u0632 4 \u0645\u0627\u0647\u0648\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u0628\u0648\u0645\u06cc\u060c\u200c \u0645\u0648\u062a\u0648\u0631 \u0645\u0627\u0647\u0648\u0627\u0631\u0647\u200c\u0628\u0631 \"\u0633\u0641\u06cc\u0631B1 \" \u0648 \"\u0643\u0627\u0648\u0634\u06af\u06314 \"|publisher=Tebyan.net|accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://presstv.com/detail/224597.htm|title=No Operation |publisher=Presstv.com|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115165554/http://presstv.com/detail/224597.htm|archive-date=15 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"ayenehnashriat.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ayenehnashriat.com/Pages/News-2661.html|title=Archived copy|accessdate=25 March 2011|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110904200632/http://www.ayenehnashriat.com/Pages/News-2661.html|archivedate=4 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mehrnews.com/fa/newsdetail.aspx?NewsID=1252012|title=Iran, world, political, sport, economic news and headlines|publisher=MehrNews.com|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714070510/http://www.mehrnews.com/fa/newsdetail.aspx?NewsID=1252012|archive-date=14 July 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> The satellite will be sent into a [[geostationary orbit]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail/2014/01/06/344130/iran-developing-zafar-sat-space-model/|title=Archived copy|accessdate=30 January 2014|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701200924/http://www.presstv.ir/detail/2014/01/06/344130/iran-developing-zafar-sat-space-model/|archivedate=1 July 2015}}</ref> The launcher is expected to be a Simorgh missile.<ref name=\"english.farsnews.com\"/>\n\n* [[Mesbah]] (meaning 'Lantern') was to be built by Iran in collaboration with Italy's [http://www.cgspace.it/ Carlo Gavazzi Space S.p.A]. Mesbah was a [[Low Earth orbit]] [[telecommunication satellite]]. The satellite was never launched as both Russia and Italy refused to cooperate with Iran anymore on space projects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://presstv.com/detail/173346.html|title=Iran to retrieve Mesbah-1 sat from Italy|publisher=Press TV|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316190052/http://www.presstv.com/detail/173346.html|archive-date=16 March 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The original Mesbah project was later on replaced by indigenous [[Mesbah-2]] which is to be built and launched by Iran alone.<ref name=\"chinadaily.com.cn\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/world/2009-11/21/content_9015504.htm |title=Iran to launch satellite on its own by late 2011|work=China Daily|date=21 November 2009|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110125235234/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/world/2009-11/21/content_9015504.htm|archive-date=25 January 2011|url-status=live }}</ref> It was reported, in April 2011, that the US$10 million satellite built in Italy, has not been delivered to Iran. Italy has refused to hand over the satellite to Iran under the pretext of [[Sanctions against Iran|international sanctions on Iran]]. Iran maintains that the satellite be handed over for its launch by an Iranian satellite carrier.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zawya.com/story.cfm/sidANA20110405T123153ZFWD18|title=Zawya|publisher=Zawya |accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=BaniComm Co.|url=http://www.isna.ir/ISNA/NewsView.aspx?ID=News-1741444&Lang=E|title=ISNA \u2013 04-05-2011 \u2013 90/1/16 \u2013 Service: / Science / News ID: 1741444 |publisher=Isna.ir|accessdate=6 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120802170921/http://www.isna.ir/ISNA/NewsView.aspx?ID=News-1741444&Lang=E|archivedate=2 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.trend.az/regions/iran/1856293.html|title=Iranian official: Italy deviates from handing over Misbah satellite \u2013 Trend|publisher=En.trend.az|date=5 April 2011|accessdate=6 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903072346/http://en.trend.az/regions/iran/1856293.html|archive-date=3 September 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n* [[Mesbah-2]] is a limited application communication satellite which was conceived as a locally designed satellite after the original [[Mesbah]] project failed to materialize due to international pressures on Iran. It will have a life span of 3 years with store dump capability and its own navigation system. It is scheduled for launch in 2012.<ref name=\"globalsecurity.org\"/><ref name=\"google.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jCDd1NvNvsNUIU4Us1P-aYbvT9HA|title=AFP: Iran to unveil three new home-built satellites: report|publisher=Google|date=20 January 2010|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429164444/http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jCDd1NvNvsNUIU4Us1P-aYbvT9HA|archive-date=29 April 2011|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"payvand.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/10/feb/1025.html|title=Iran unveils three new home-made satellites|publisher=Payvand.com|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316232028/http://www.payvand.com/news/10/feb/1025.html|archive-date=16 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"chinadaily.com.cn\"/>\n\n* [[Qaem (satellite)|Qaem]], is a [[geosynchronous satellite|geosynchronous communication satellite]] that is being developed by Iran and is scheduled to be launched on an Iranian carrier by 2016. The satellite is going to have a life expectancy of 15 years, broadcasting TV and Radio channels.<ref name=\"isa.ir\">{{cite web|author=Sina Shafigh|url=http://www.isa.ir/components1.php?rQV==wHQxAkOklUZnFWdn5WYMJXZ0VWbhJXYw9lZ8BkN1QDQ6QWStVGdp9lZ8BUM4ATMApDZJ52bpR3Yh9lZ|title=\u0633\u0627\u0632\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0641\u0636\u0627\u06cc\u06cc \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646|publisher=Isa.ir|accessdate=6 February 2012|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421104347/http://www.isa.ir/components1.php?rQV==wHQxAkOklUZnFWdn5WYMJXZ0VWbhJXYw9lZ8BkN1QDQ6QWStVGdp9lZ8BUM4ATMApDZJ52bpR3Yh9lZ|archivedate=21 April 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"sri.ac.ir\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sri.ac.ir/index.aspx?siteid=1&pageid=141&newsview=19|title=\u0633\u0627\u064a\u062a \u0627\u0635\u0644\u064a - \u0627\u062e\u0628\u0627\u0631\u0648 \u0631\u0648\u064a\u062f\u0627\u062f\u0647\u0627|publisher=Sri.ac.ir|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316094724/http://www.sri.ac.ir/index.aspx?siteid=1&pageid=141&newsview=19|archive-date=16 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n* [[Pars Sepehr]], is a remote sensing satellite being built and to be launched from Iran. Its launch date is not yet confirmed.<ref name=\"isa.ir\"/><ref name=\"sri.ac.ir\"/>\n\n* [[Pars-2]], is a remote sensing satellite being built and to be launched from Iran. Its launch schedule has not yet been announced.<ref name=\"isa.ir\"/><ref name=\"sri.ac.ir\"/>\n\n* [[ZS4]] is an Iranian satellite to be launched by an Iranian launcher. Its mission role and launch date have not been revealed.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Book: ''Iran: Development \u2013 space launch systems and satellites'', By: Brian Harvey, Henk H. F. Smid and Th\u00e9o Pirard.</ref><ref name=\"spatialsource.com.au\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spatialsource.com.au/article/Irans-Space-Ambitions/ZETSPMAZSF.html?page%3D3 |title=Archived copy|accessdate=21 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110306002712/http://www.spatialsource.com.au/article/Irans-Space-Ambitions/ZETSPMAZSF.html?page=3 |archivedate=6 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://parviztarikhi.files.wordpress.com/2010/02/heading2space.pdf|title=Archived copy|accessdate=21 May 2012|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315153403/https://parviztarikhi.files.wordpress.com/2010/02/heading2space.pdf|archivedate=15 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n* [[Sina-2]] is a small satellite that will replace the mission role of [[Sina-1]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref name=\"spatialsource.com.au\"/>\n\n* [[SM2S]] is an Iranian satellite to be launched by an Iranian launcher. Its mission role and launch date have not been revealed.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref>http://iran.ru/eng/iran_news.php?act=news_by_id&news_id=20655{{dead link|date=December 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref>\n\n* Iran is also to implement 10 satellite projects with [[Asia-Pacific Space Cooperation Organization]] (APSCO) members. The organization has defined 10 projects on designing, building and launching light satellites, middle class satellites weighing 500\u2013600 kg, research satellites, remote-sensing and telecommunications satellites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/10/oct/1160.html|title=Iran to implement 10 satellite projects with APSCO members|publisher=Payvand.com |accessdate=6 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120812210104/http://www.payvand.com/news/10/oct/1160.html |archive-date=12 August 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/11/apr/1022.html|title=Iran plans to join APSCO satellite-building project|publisher=Payvand.com|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120904233927/http://www.payvand.com/news/11/apr/1022.html|archive-date=4 September 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n* [[Besharat (satellite)|Besharat]] satellite is being built by Iran with collaboration of some [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation|OIC]] members which have volunteered in the project. It is to be launched by Iran. The countries which are jointly working with Iran on the project are Pakistan, Turkey, Malaysia and some Arab countries. Its launch date is not yet confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|author=John Pike |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/space/world/iran/safir-1-2.htm|title=Iran Space Launch Vehicles|publisher=Globalsecurity.org|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104090533/http://www.globalsecurity.org/space/world/iran/safir-1-2.htm|archive-date=4 November 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.payvand.com/news/08/aug/1223.html|title=Iran, OIC to build satellite 'Besharat'|publisher=Payvand.com|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120904233933/http://www.payvand.com/news/08/aug/1223.html|archive-date=4 September 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iran-daily.com/1384/2408/html/economy.htm|title=Internet Archive Wayback Machine|publisher=Web.archive.org|date=10 December 2007|accessdate=6 February 2012|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207115701/http://www.iran-daily.com/1384/2408/html/economy.htm|archivedate=7 February 2009}}</ref>\n\n* [[Saar (satellite)|Saar (Starling)]] will be produced by Iran's [[K.N.Toosi University of Technology|Khajeh Nasir Toosi University of Technology]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.presstv.com/detail/2012/07/30/253468/iran-to-build-new-indigenous-satellite/|title=Archived copy|accessdate=1 August 2012|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120801033928/http://www.presstv.com/detail/2012/07/30/253468/iran-to-build-new-indigenous-satellite/|archivedate=1 August 2012}}</ref> No further details have been given.\n\n* [[Zohreh]], is a [[geosynchronous satellite|geosynchronous communication satellite]] which was originally proposed before the Revolution in the 1970s as part of a joint Indian-Iranian project of four Iranian satellites to be launched by the then upcoming [[NASA]] [[space shuttle]]s. Iran had also negotiated with France to build and launch the satellites but the project never materialized. In 2005, Iran negotiated with Russia to build and launch the first Zohreh satellite under an agreement worth $132 million with the satellite launch date stipulated as 2007\u20132008. The new agreement had followed the earlier failed negotiations with Russia in 2003 when Russia cancelled the project under US pressures. The satellite was to be of [[Ekspress|Express-1000]] type and capable of relaying telephone, fax, data and television signals with a life span of 15 years.<ref name=\"spacedaily.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inss.org.il/publications.php?cat=21&incat=&read=160&print=1|title=The Institute for National Security Studies |publisher=INSS|date=27 October 2005|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326084549/http://www.inss.org.il/publications.php?cat=21&incat=&read=160&print=1|archive-date=26 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=John Pike|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/space/world/iran/zohreh.htm|title=Zohreh|publisher=Globalsecurity.org|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207110332/http://www.globalsecurity.org/space/world/iran/zohreh.htm|archive-date=7 February 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2010, Iran announced that it will build and launch the satellite locally as the foreign contractors had refused to complete the project. New launch date for the satellite was announced as 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peymane.ir/fa/pages/?cid=25045|title=\u0645\u0627\u0647\u0648\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u0632\u0647\u0631\u0647 \u062a\u0627 \u0686\u0647\u0627\u0631\u0633\u0627\u0644 \u0622\u064a\u0646\u062f\u0647 \u0628\u0647 \u0641\u0636\u0627 \u067e\u0631\u062a\u0627\u0628 \u0645\u064a \u0634\u0648\u062f|publisher=Peymane.ir|accessdate=6 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316094724/http://www.peymane.ir/fa/pages/?cid=25045|archivedate=16 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Behnegarsoft.com|url=http://alef.ir/1388/content/view/84900/|title=\u0627\u0644\u0641 - \u067e\u0631\u062a\u0627\u0628 \u0645\u0627\u0647\u0648\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u0632\u0647\u0631\u0647 \u062a\u0627 4 \u0633\u0627\u0644 \u0622\u064a\u0646\u062f\u0647|publisher=Alef.ir|accessdate=6 February 2012 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005181956/http://alef.ir/1388/content/view/84900/|archivedate=5 October 2011}}</ref> Russia had announced in 2009 that it is not going to cooperate with Iran on any space projects but reversed course again following the lifting of international [[sanctions against Iran]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last=Weinberger|first=Sharon |url=https://www.wired.com/dangerroom/2009/06/russians-say-nyet-to-another-iranian-satellite/|title=Russians Say 'Nyet' To Another Iranian Satellite &#124; Danger Room|work=Wired|date=25 June 2009|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120115041637/http://www.wired.com/dangerroom/2009/06/russians-say-nyet-to-another-iranian-satellite|archive-date=15 January 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allourmight.com/?p=674|title=Blog Archive \u00bb Iran/Russia and arms sales, pre-Obama visit|publisher=All Our Might|date=26 June 2009|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325222755/http://www.allourmight.com/?p=674|archive-date=25 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azernews.az/region/106464.html|title=Archived copy|accessdate=14 December 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161229110433/http://www.azernews.az/region/106464.html|archivedate=29 December 2016}}</ref> Iran has also solicited [[NASA]]'s cooperation in future space projects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/irans-space-agency-eyes-cooperation-with-nasa/|title=Archived copy|accessdate=4 December 2016|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221011036/http://www.timesofisrael.com/irans-space-agency-eyes-cooperation-with-nasa/|archivedate=21 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Space centers ==\n{{Main|Imam Khomeini Spaceport}}\n{{See also|List of space agencies|List of rocket launch sites}}\n{{kml}}\n\nThe main launch site of the [[Iranian Space Agency]] is [[Shahrud, Iran|Shahrud]], located at {{Coord|36|25|0|N|55|01|0|E|name=Iranian Space Agency Emamshahr|type:landmark_region:IR_scale:10000}}, where suborbital [[Shahab 3]]s LV have been launched.\n\n[[Qom]], located at {{Coord|34|39|0|N|50|54|0|E|name=Iranian Space Agency Qom|type:landmark_region:IR_scale:10000}}, is the other launch site.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/iran-builds-space-center-launch-satellites-125730061.html;_ylt=A2KJjagamcpPhiYAag3QtDMD|title=Archived copy|accessdate=3 June 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305081945/http://news.yahoo.com/iran-builds-space-center-launch-satellites-125730061.html%3B_ylt%3DA2KJjagamcpPhiYAag3QtDMD|archivedate=5 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn occasion of the inaugural launch of Iran's first [[Safir (rocket)|Safir-class]] sub-orbital rocket called [[Kavoshgar-1]] (Explorer-1), Iran unveiled on 4 February 2008, its first Satellite Launch Center {{Coord|35.234|N|53.921|E|name=Iranian Space Agency Satellite Launch Center Semnan|type:landmark_region:IR_scale:10000}} in [[Semnan, Iran|Semnan city]]. The facility includes an underground command and control center, a tracking station and a launchpad among other structures.\n\nIn December 2010, it was announced that due to geographical limitations of first space center in injecting satellite into orbit, studies have been carried out for setting up a second (satellite) launch pad.<ref name=\"presstv.ir\">{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail/155116.html|title=No Operation|publisher=Press TV|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011172937/http://www.presstv.ir/detail/155116.html|archive-date=11 October 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The new national [[spaceport]] of Iran, named after [[Imam Khomeini]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/12/jun/1015.html|title=Archived copy|accessdate=3 June 2012|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304204457/http://www.payvand.com/news/12/jun/1015.html|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref> is being built in Semnan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7oSVX6mkmds|title=Archived copy|accessdate=24 January 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161207040605/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7oSVX6mkmds|archivedate=7 December 2016}}</ref> \n\nThis new port is to be used to launch all future Iranian space missions similar to American [[Kennedy Space Center]] or the [[Baikonur Cosmodrome]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mashreghnews.ir/NSite/FullStory/News/?Id=34283|title=\u062a\u0627\u0633\u064a\u0633 \u067e\u0627\u064a\u06af\u0627\u0647 \u0645\u0644\u064a \u067e\u0631\u062a\u0627\u0628 \u0645\u0627\u0647\u0648\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u062f\u0631\u062c\u0646\u0648\u0628 \u0634\u0631\u0642 \u06a9\u0634\u0648\u0631 - \u0645\u0634\u0631\u0642 \u0646\u06cc\u0648\u0632|publisher=mashreghnews.ir|date=15 June 2011|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320152924/http://www.mashreghnews.ir/NSite/FullStory/News/?Id=34283|archive-date=20 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>http://baztab.jetjoin.com/2011/03/11/%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%B3%DB%8C%D8%B3-%D9%BE%D8%A7%DB%8C%DA%AF%D8%A7%D9%87-%D9%85%D9%84%DB%8C-%D9%BE%D8%B1%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%A8-%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%87%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%87-%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%AC%D9%86%D9%88%D8%A8/{{dead link|date=December 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ihrc.ir/FA/NewsShow.aspx?ID=8141|title=\u0627\u062e\u062a\u0635\u0627\u0635 \u06f4 \u0645\u064a\u0644\u064a\u0627\u0631\u062f \u062a\u0648\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0639\u062a\u0628\u0627\u0631 \u0628\u0631\u0627\u064a \u0633\u0627\u062e\u062a \u0627\u0628\u0631\u0631\u0627\u064a\u0627\u0646\u0647 \u0645\u0644\u064a|publisher=Ihrc.ir|accessdate=6 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110818084219/http://ihrc.ir/FA/NewsShow.aspx?ID=8141|archivedate=18 August 2011}}</ref> In March 2011, [[Jane's Information Group]] reported on the basis of its satellite imagery analysis of Iranian space launch sites that Iran is aggressively building complex facilities with very rapid pace showing the nation's inclinations towards space readiness.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.janes.com/articles/Janes-Defence-Weekly-2011/Iran-accelerates-space-and-missile-launch-projects.html|title=Iran accelerates space and missile launch projects \u2013 Jane's Defence Weekly|publisher=Articles.janes.com|date=18 March 2011|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503102555/http://articles.janes.com/articles/Janes-Defence-Weekly-2011/Iran-accelerates-space-and-missile-launch-projects.html|archive-date=3 May 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2013, Iran inaugurated its first space monitoring center located near Delijan in Markazi province, according to Iran's Defense Minister General Ahmad Vahidi the new center which was named Imam Ja'far Sadeq would mostly be used to track and detect space objects and satellites passing overhead using radar, electro-optic and radio systems.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.farsnews.com/newstext.php?nn%3D9203180420|title=Archived copy|accessdate=9 June 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130613054423/http://english.farsnews.com/newstext.php?nn=9203180420|archivedate=13 June 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.farsnews.com/imgrep.php?nn%3D13920319000829|title=Archived copy|accessdate=9 June 2013|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304045552/http://www.farsnews.com/imgrep.php?nn=13920319000829|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rt.com/news/iran-space-monitoring-center-429/|title=Archived copy|accessdate=9 June 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160526185603/https://www.rt.com/news/iran-space-monitoring-center-429/|archivedate=26 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Space test laboratory ==\n{{See also|Iranian Space Research Center|Science and technology in Iran}}\n\nIn 2011, Iran launched a number of laboratories for testing \"space structures and systems\" in line with its progressing space program. The laboratory includes ten labs to \"reinforce infrastructures of Iran's space industry\" and help improve the abilities of human resources.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail/162692.html|title=Archived copy|accessdate=15 March 2011|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011173023/http://www.presstv.ir/detail/162692.html|archivedate=11 October 2012}}</ref>{{clarify|date=February 2012|reason=source is too vague \u2013 what does it mean by \"laboratories\" and \"launch\"? Please clarify and reword this to serve an encyclopedia purpose}}\n\n== Manned space program ==\n{{Main|Iranian manned spaceship project}}\n\nIran expressed for the first time its intention to send a human to space during the summit of Soviet and Iranian Presidents at 21 June 1990. [[President of the Soviet Union|Soviet President]] [[Mikhail Gorbachev]] reached an agreement in principle with then-President [[Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani]] to make joint Soviet-Iranian manned flights to [[Mir space station]] but this agreement was never realized after the breakup of the [[Soviet Union]].\n\nAlmost two decades later the [[IRNA|Iranian News Agency]] claimed on 21 November 2005, that the Iranians have a manned space program along with plans for the development of a spacecraft and a space laboratory. <!--do not delete! Chinese IRNA link when first accessed<ref>[http://www.irna.ir/ch/news/view/menu-332/0511213283154918.html]</ref>--><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSBLA13323720080821 |title=Iran plans manned space mission in 10 years|agency=Reuters|date=21 August 2008|accessdate=6 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722041036/http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSBLA13323720080821|archive-date=22 July 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Iran Aerospace Industries Organization]] (IAIO) head Reza Taghipour on 20 August 2008, revealed Iran intends to launch a manned mission into space within a decade. This goal was described as the country's top priority for the next 10 years, in order to make Iran the leading space power of the region by 2021.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3585540,00.html|title=First Iranian in space within decade|publisher=[[Ynetnews]]|date=20 August 2008|accessdate=20 August 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080824010221/http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3585540,00.html|archive-date=24 August 2008|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.rian.ru/world/20080820/116164664.html|title=Iran to send first astronaut into space within 10 years|agency=RIA Novosti|date=20 August 2008|accessdate=11 September 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080909235859/http://en.rian.ru/world/20080820/116164664.html|archive-date=9 September 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2010, President Ahmadinejad announced that Iran's first astronaut should be sent into space on board an Iranian spacecraft by no later than 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-10747390|work=BBC News|title=Iran aims to send man into space by 2019|date=23 July 2010|access-date=21 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125130121/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-10747390|archive-date=25 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.com/detail.aspx?id%3D135966%26sectionid%3D351020101|title=Archived copy|accessdate=23 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304003240/http://www.presstv.com/detail.aspx?id=135966&sectionid=351020101|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref> Later on in December 2010, Iranian Communications and Information Technology Minister [[Reza Taghipour]] stated that \"The initial steps for the plan have been taken, and the study phase on the definition of subsystems, sub-projects, costs, and what projects need to be developed toward that end, has been conducted, which needs to be submitted to the Supreme Council on Space\".<ref name=\"presstv.ir\"/> According to Iranian manned space program, the first [[sub-orbital spaceflight]] was take place by 2016 at an altitude below 200 kilometers as preparation for the eventual [[orbital spaceflight]].<ref name=ISA-suborbit>{{cite web|url=http://www.isa.ir/components1.php?rQV==wHQyAkOklUZnFWdn5WYMJXZ0VWbhJXYw9lZ8B0N3QDQ6QWStVGdp9lZ8BUM4ATMApDZJ52bpR3Yh9lZ |title=Dispatching Iranian astronaut to below 200 km orbit|publisher=Iranian Space Agency|date=31 May 2011|accessdate=29 December 2012|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224101258/http://www.isa.ir/components1.php?rQV==wHQyAkOklUZnFWdn5WYMJXZ0VWbhJXYw9lZ8B0N3QDQ6QWStVGdp9lZ8BUM4ATMApDZJ52bpR3Yh9lZ|archivedate=24 December 2013}}</ref> No such vehicle was developed.\n\nOn 17 February 2015, Iran unveiled a mock [[prototype]] of [[Iranian manned spaceship project|Iranian manned spaceship]] that would capable of taking astronauts into space.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.payvand.com/news/15/feb/1087.html|title=Archived copy|accessdate=22 February 2015|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304204646/http://www.payvand.com/news/15/feb/1087.html|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref> According to Iran's Space Administrator, this program was put on hold in 2017 indefinitely.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/31/world/middleeast/iran-space.html|title=Iran Drops Plan to Send Human into Space, Citing Cost|last=GLADSTONE|first=RICK|access-date=1 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170601065046/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/31/world/middleeast/iran-space.html|archive-date=1 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Space station ===\nAccording to unofficial Chinese internet sources, an Iranian participation in the future [[Chinese space program#Space station|Chinese space station]] program has been discussed. This involvement might range from simply sending astronauts to the 60 tons class space station to contributing with development of a space laboratory module. International manned space cooperation has officially been disclosed for the first time after the launch of the Chinese [[Shenzhou 7]] spacecraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/newscenter/2008-09/26/content_10114727.htm|title=\u6743\u5a01\u53d1\u5e03:\u795e\u821f\u98de\u8239\u5c06\u4ece\u795e\u516b\u5f00\u59cb\u6279\u91cf\u751f\u4ea7|publisher=\u65b0\u534e\u7f51|date=26 September 2008|accessdate=26 September 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080929025036/http://news.xinhuanet.com/newscenter/2008-09/26/content_10114727.htm|archivedate=29 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n=== Lunar program ===\nWestern media has quoted that Iran has plans to land an astronaut on the Moon by 2025. Currently Iran doesn't have a medium lift rocket, therefore as of now Iran sending a human to space is unlikely due to the lack of equipment.<ref name=ISA-suborbit/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ieet.org/index.php/IEET/more/nicholas20120405|title=Archived copy|accessdate=5 April 2012|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160908095840/http://ieet.org/index.php/IEET/more/nicholas20120405|archivedate=8 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.space.com/13270-iran-space-monkey-launch-failure.html|title=Archived copy|accessdate=8 September 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224030624/http://www.space.com/13270-iran-space-monkey-launch-failure.html |archivedate=24 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn22136-iran-space-agency-to-launch-a-monkey-into-space.html|title=Iran Space Agency to launch a monkey into space \u2013 space \u2013 03 August 2012 \u2013 New Scientist|accessdate=7 September 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701195840/http://www.newscientist.com/article/dn22136-iran-space-agency-to-launch-a-monkey-into-space.html|archivedate=1 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=Harding>{{cite book|last=Harding|first=Robert C.|title=Space Policy in Developing Countries: The Search for Security and Development on the Final Frontier|date=2012|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-53845-9|page=131}}</ref><ref name=Lele>{{cite book|last=Lele|first=Ajey|title=Asian Space Race: Rhetoric or Reality?|date=2012|publisher=Springer |isbn=978-8132207320|edition=2013|page=33}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\n{{See also|Nuclear program of Iran}}\n\nThe Iranian space program has been condemned by United States and Europe because of their concern over its military potential. Some analysts have compared the relatively fast Iranian advancement in space technology to Russia's [[Sputnik program]] with the prediction that this advancement will propel Iran's military capability in other areas as well. The military concerns over Iran's space program has been exacerbated over Safir rocket's advanced 2nd stage which Iran has kept secret by not releasing any technical information related to the second stage of the rocket, keeping outside observers guessing over the technicalities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://meria.idc.ac.il/journal/2006/issue3/jv10no3a2.html|title=Iran's Space Program: The Next Genie in a Bottle?|publisher=Meria.idc.ac.il|accessdate=6 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111227052716/http://meria.idc.ac.il/journal/2006/issue3/jv10no3a2.html|archivedate=27 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://biak-spaceport.blogspot.com/2010/02/emerging-iranian-space-program.html|title=Biak Spaceport: The Emerging Iranian Space Program|publisher=Biak-spaceport.blogspot.com|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316094747/http://biak-spaceport.blogspot.com/2010/02/emerging-iranian-space-program.html|archive-date=16 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=3934643{{dead link|date=December 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spacewar.com/reports/Iranian_missiles_have_worldwide_reach_Russia_999.html|title=Iranian missiles have 'worldwide reach': Russia|publisher=Spacewar.com|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207120524/http://www.spacewar.com/reports/Iranian_missiles_have_worldwide_reach_Russia_999.html|archive-date=7 February 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/02/03/world/main4771491.shtml?source=RSSattr=HOME_4771491|publisher=CBS News|title=Iran Launches First Homegrown Satellite|date=3 February 2009|access-date=30 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214055515/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/02/03/world/main4771491.shtml?source=RSSattr=HOME_4771491|archive-date=14 February 2009|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.asemangasht.com/travel_news/show.php?id=24|title=Travel News \u2013 Iran claims first launch of its own satellite|publisher=Asemangasht.com|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317012937/http://www.asemangasht.com/travel_news/show.php?id=24|archive-date=17 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/iran/2575063/Iran-launches-rocket-capable-of-carrying-satellite.html|location=London|work=The Daily Telegraph|first=Our|last=Foreign|title=Iran launches rocket capable of carrying satellite|date=17 August 2008|access-date=5 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907182945/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/iran/2575063/Iran-launches-rocket-capable-of-carrying-satellite.html|archive-date=7 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> For Radio Free Europe, independent experts interviewed disagreed with assertion made by the U.S. and various European countries. [[Stockholm International Peace Research Institute|SIPRI's]] Tytti Er\u00e4st\u00f6 stated space launch vehicle program can contribute to missile development yet it isn't a shortcut for development of long range missiles such as intercontinental ballistic missiles, historically the ICBMs were converted to SLVs and never was in history SLV converted to ICBM. [[International Institute for Strategic Studies|IISS]] Michael Elleman stated that claims made by the U.S. such as [[Mike Pompeo]] are grossly exaggerating contribution of SLV program to ICBM program and that it is misguided to suggest that SLV program is cover for nuclear capable ICBMs as claims made are a political statement. ST Analytics Markus Schiller stated that there is no indication that Iran is trying to develop missiles with range longer than 2000 km as Iran has been working on improving accuracy of their existing short and medium range missiles.<ref>https://www.rferl.org/a/is-iran-converting-space-launchers-into-long-range-missiles-/30437113.html</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Iran|Science|Spaceflight}}\n\n* [[Aerospace Force of the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]]\n* [[Anousheh Ansari]] \u2013 First [[Iranian-American]] cosmonaut\n* [[Colonization of Mars]]\n* [[Colonization of the Moon]]\n* [[Economy of Iran]]\n* [[International rankings of Iran#Science and technology|International rankings of Iran in science and technology]]\n* [[Iran Aviation Industries Organization]]\n* [[Timeline of first orbital launches by country#List of first orbital launches by country|List of first orbital launches by country]]\n* [[List of government space agencies]]\n* [[List of Iranian research centers]]\n* [[List of missions to the Moon]]\n* [[Human spaceflight#National spacefaring attempts|National spacefaring programs]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.isa.ir/ Iranian Space Agency]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070418150218/http://www.spacescience.ir/ Space Science]\n* [http://www.globalsecurity.org/space/world/iran/agency.htm Iranian Space Agencies (listing)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110406115504/http://www.astronautix.com/country/iran.htm Iran space program]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060615142503/http://astronautix.com/lvs/shaabslv.htm Shahab SLV]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090216100124/http://aio.ir/ Aerospace Industries Organization]\n* [http://www.globalsecurity.org/space/world/iran/index.html Iran in Space] Globalsecurity.org\n\n;Videos\n* [http://presstv.com/Detail/2016/11/16/493845/Iran-aerospace-achievements A glimpse of Iran\u2019s latest aerospace achievements] \u2013 [[PressTV]] (2016)\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7oSVX6mkmds Imam Khomeini Space Center \u2013 Iran] \u2013 [[Nuclear Threat Initiative]] (2013)\n* {{YouTube|8OKu04fYgTk|Video on Iran Space Program}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/PressTVGlobalNews#p/u/8/JPKzGVGUVPw Iran's space technology program \u2013 Part I] [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ac8JPUXx640 Part II] [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E2FF0Cvb7J8 Part III] \u2013 [[PressTV]]\n\n{{Iranian Space Program}}\n{{Public sector space agencies}}\n{{Space exploration lists and timelines}}\n\n[[Category:Space program of Iran]]\n[[Category:Government agencies of Iran]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 2003]]\n[[Category:2003 establishments in Iran]]\n[[Category:Science and technology in Iran]]\n[[Category:Scientific organisations based in Iran]]\n[[Category:Space agencies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox space agency\n| name          = Iranian Space Agency<br />(ISA)\n| acronym       = ISA\n| image         = Iranian Space Agency logo.png\n| size          = 150px\n| caption       = Official logo of ISA\n\n| spaceport     = [[Imam Khomeini Spaceport]]\n| established   = {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|mf=no|2004|2|1}}\n| owner         = [[Ministry of Information and Communications Technology (Iran)|Ministry of Communications and Information Technology]], Iran\n| headquarters  = [[Tehran]], [[Mahdasht]], [[Shahrud]], [[Qom]]\n| budget        = $4.6 million (FY 2017)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://financialtribune.com/articles/sci-tech/55397/cuts-and-extensions-in-irans-ict-201718-budget|title=Cuts and Extensions in Iran's ICT 2017/18 Budget|date=14 December 2016|work=Financial Tribune|accessdate=11 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220150555/https://financialtribune.com/articles/sci-tech/55397/cuts-and-extensions-in-irans-ict-201718-budget|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| administrator = [[Morteza Barari]]\n| URL           = {{URL|www.isa.ir}}\n}}\n{{Spaceflight sidebar}}\n\nThe '''Iranian Space Agency''' ('''ISA''', [[Persian language|Persian]]: {{lang|fa|\u0633\u0627\u0632\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0641\u0636\u0627\u06cc\u06cc \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646}} ''S\u0101zm\u0101ne Faz\u0101iye Ir\u0101n'') is [[Iran]]'s [[Government of Iran|governmental]] [[space agency]].\nIran became an [[Timeline of first orbital launches by country|orbital-launch-capable nation]] in 2009.<ref name=ptv20120203/> Iran is one of the 24 founding members of the [[United Nations Committee on the Peaceful Uses of Outer Space]] (COPUOS), which was set up on 13 December 1958.<ref name=ptv20120203>{{cite web|url=http://presstv.com/detail/224597.html|title=Iran to establish national satellite launch base |publisher=Press TV|date=3 February 2012|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303230604/http://presstv.com/detail/224597.html|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nISA was established on 28 February 2004, according to the Article 9 of the Law for Tasks and Authorizations of the [[Ministry of Information and Communications Technology of Iran|Ministry of Communications and Information Technology]] passed on 10 December 2003 by the [[Parliament of Iran]]. Based on the approved statute ISA mandated to cover and support all the activities in Iran concerning the peaceful applications of space science and technology under the leadership of a Supreme Council of Space chaired by the [[President of Iran]].\n\nThe Council's main goals included policy making for the application of space technologies aiming peaceful uses of outer space, manufacturing, launching and use of the national research satellites, approving the space related state and private sector programs, promoting the partnership of the private and cooperative sectors in efficient uses of space, identifying guidelines concerning the regional and international cooperation in space issues.\n\nTo follow and implement the strategies set by the Council, ISA affiliated with the [[Ministry of Information and Communications Technology of Iran|Ministry of Communication and Information Technology]] in the form of an autonomous organization, was organized. The president of ISA held the position of the Vice-Minister of Communications and Information Technology and the secretariat of Supreme Council of Space at the same time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://parviztarikhi.wordpress.com/features-2/more-significant-role-for-iran%e2%80%99s-space-administration|title=More significant role for Iran\u2019s space administration|publisher=Parviz Tarikhi|date=11 November 2010|accessdate=17 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718103724/http://parviztarikhi.wordpress.com/features-2/more-significant-role-for-iran%e2%80%99s-space-administration/ |archive-date=18 July 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSince 2015, Iran's space program has been quietly suspended by [[President Rouhani]] following international pressures.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://warisboring.com/iran-just-cancelled-its-space-program-5b1d5ce50bd6|title=Archived copy|accessdate=24 September 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925012918/https://warisboring.com/iran-just-cancelled-its-space-program-5b1d5ce50bd6 |archivedate=25 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Budget ==\n{{See also|Politics of Iran#Budget}}\n\nThe proposed budget for the Iranian year [[Iranian calendars|1393]] (2014\u20132015) is 1,865,583 million rials (US$71,753,192). Other related organizations have received separate budget allocations. [[Iranian Space Research Center]] has received an additional 1,751,000 million rials (US$67,346,100) of budget for the year 1393.<ref>{{cite book|title=Budget Bill of 1393 (\u0644\u0627\u064a\u062d\u0647 \u0628\u0648\u062f\u062c\u0647 \u0633\u0627\u0644 1393 \u0643\u0644 \u0643\u0634\u0648\u0631)|publisher=Secretariat of Planning and Supervision, Office of President|date=December 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe budget for the year 2008 was mentioned to be US$3.9 billion (2008).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aftab.ir/news/view/2008/feb/20/c2c1203499802_economy_marketing_business_information_technology_mobile.php |title=\u0627\u062e\u062a\u0635\u0627\u0635 \u06f3 \u0647\u0632\u0627\u0631 \u0648 \u06f9\u06f6\u06f0 \u0645\u06cc\u0644\u06cc\u0627\u0631\u062f \u062a\u0648\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u0631\u0627\u06cc \u0633\u0627\u0632\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0641\u0636\u0627\u06cc\u06cc \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646|agency=[[Aftab News Agency]]|date=February 2008|accessdate=17 January 2011}}</ref> However it was not apparent whether the allocation was just for one year or a longer period.\n\nUnder president [[Hassan Rouhani]], the proposed 2017-budget for the Iranian Space Agency fell to a low of US$4.6 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://financialtribune.com/articles/sci-tech/55397/cuts-and-extensions-in-irans-ict-201718-budget|title=Archived copy|accessdate=14 December 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220150555/https://financialtribune.com/articles/sci-tech/55397/cuts-and-extensions-in-irans-ict-201718-budget|archivedate=20 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Satellite launch vehicle (SLV) ==\n{{Main|Safir (rocket)|Simorgh (rocket)}}\n[[File:Noor_satellite.jpg|thumb|Noor satellite launch]]\n\n=== Safir SLV ===\nIran has developed an expendable satellite launch vehicle named [[Safir (rocket)|Safir SLV]]. Measuring 22 m in height with a core diameter of 1.25 m, with two liquid propellant stages, a single thrust chambered first stage and a two-thrust chambered, step-throttled second stage, the SLV has a lift off mass exceeding 26 tons. The first stage consists of a lengthened up-rated [[Shahab-3C]]. According to the technical documentation presented in the annual meeting of the [[United Nations Office for Outer Space Affairs]], it is a two-stage rocket with all liquid propellant engines. The first stage is capable of carrying the payload to the maximum altitude of 68 kilometers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oosa.unvienna.org/pdf/pres/stsc2009/tech-15.pdf|title=Archived copy|accessdate=15 March 2009|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905233838/http://www.oosa.unvienna.org/pdf/pres/stsc2009/tech-15.pdf|archivedate=5 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== Safir-1B ====\nThe Safir-1B is the second generation of Safir SLV and can carry a satellite weighing 60 kg into an [[Elliptic orbit|elliptical orbit]] of 300 to 450 km. The thrust of the Safir-1B rocket engine has been increased from 32 to 37 tons.\n\n=== Simorgh SLV ===\nIn 2010, a more powerful rocket named [[Simorgh (rocket)|Simorgh]] (Phoenix) was built. Its mission is to carry heavier satellites into orbit.<ref name=\"payvand1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.payvand.com/news/10/feb/1025.html|title=Iran unveils three new home-made satellites|publisher=Payvand.com|date=22 November 2006|accessdate=6 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100206215559/http://www.payvand.com/news/10/feb/1025.html|archive-date=6 February 2010|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tehrantimes.com/index_View.asp?code=213671|title=Iran launches spacecraft carrying animals / Space program breakthroughs signal the dawn of a new era of national development: Ahmadinejad|work=Tehran Times|accessdate=6 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100212225529/http://www.tehrantimes.com/index_View.asp?code=213671|archive-date=12 February 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> The Simorgh rocket is 27 meters (89 ft) long, and has a mass of 77 tonnes (85 tons).[4] Its first stage is powered by four main engines, each generating up to 29,000 kilograms (64,000 lb) of thrust, plus a fifth which will be used for [[attitude control]], which provides an additional 13,600 kilograms (30,000 lb). At liftoff, these engines will generate a total of 130,000 kilograms (290,000 lb) of thrust. Simorgh is capable of putting a 350-kilogram (770 lb) payload into a 500-kilometer (310 mi) low Earth orbit. In 2015, Israeli media reported the missile is capable of taking a manned spacecraft or satellite into space.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/israeli-tv-shows-iranian-missile-that-can-reach-far-beyond-europe/|title=Archived copy|accessdate=29 January 2015|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161225030054/http://www.timesofisrael.com/israeli-tv-shows-iranian-missile-that-can-reach-far-beyond-europe//|archivedate=25 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jerusalemonline.com/news/world-news/around-the-globe/is-iran-on-its-way-to-sending-a-man-to-outer-space-9360|title=Archived copy|accessdate=29 January 2015|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701192725/http://www.jerusalemonline.com/news/world-news/around-the-globe/is-iran-on-its-way-to-sending-a-man-to-outer-space-9360|archivedate=1 July 2015}}</ref> The first flight of the Simorgh rocket occurred on 19 April 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://defense-update.com/20160424_simorgh.html|title=Simorgh First Launch \u2013 an Iranian Success or Failure? {{!}} Defense Update:|last=Eshel|first=Tamir|website=defense-update.com|access-date=29 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161127192324/http://defense-update.com/20160424_simorgh.html|archive-date=27 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Qoqnoos SLV ===\nOn 2 February 2013, the head of the [[Iranian Space Agency]], Hamid Fazeli mentioned that the new satellite launch vehicle, Qoqnoos will be used after the Simorgh SLV for heavier payloads.<ref name=\"mehrnews1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mehrnews.com/fa/NewsDetail.aspx?NewsID=1805674|title=Details and revealing of Nahid Satellite, Launch of Nahid with Safir B-1 (Persian)|publisher=mehrnews.com|date=2 February 2013 |accessdate=3 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130205042658/http://www.mehrnews.com/fa/newsdetail.aspx?NewsID=1805674|archive-date=5 February 2013|url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"mehrnews2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mehrnews.com/en/NewsDetail.aspx?NewsID=1806425|title=Ahmadinejad to unveil Nahid Satellite soon (English)|publisher=mehrnews.com|date=2 February 2013|accessdate=3 February 2013}}{{dead link|date=November 2017|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref>\n\n== Sub-orbital launches ==\n{{See also|Science and technology in Iran}}\n\nOn 25 February 2007, the Iranian state-run television announced that a rocket, created by the ministries of science and defense and which carried an unspecified cargo, was successfully launched. This could have been the maiden test flight of the three staged [[Safir (rocket)|Safir SLV]] which ended in a failure. Later on it was noted by Iranian President [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] that the failure was due to a technical problem in the last stage of the rocket.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rDKanxOGXWk&NR=1|title=President Mahmoud Ahmadinejad \u2013 Campaign Documentary (2/4)|via=YouTube|date=31 May 2009 |accessdate=6 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140623004824/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rDKanxOGXWk&NR=1|archive-date=23 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 February 2008, Iran successfully launched a two-stage all solid-fuel sub-orbital sounding rocket [[Kavoshgar-1]] (Explorer-1), for a maiden sub-orbital test flight from [[Shahroud]], its newly inaugurated domestic space launch complex.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/7225699.stm|title=Iranians inaugurate space project|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=4 February 2008|access-date=4 February 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080209143738/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/7225699.stm|archive-date=9 February 2008|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail.aspx?id=41636&sectionid=351020101|title=Iran's Kavoshgar1 lifts off for space|publisher=[[Press TV]]|date=4 February 2008|access-date=4 February 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208120433/http://www.presstv.ir/detail.aspx?id=41636&sectionid=351020101|archive-date=8 December 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>\nThe first stage of the rocket detached after 90 seconds and returned to Earth with the help of a parachute while the second stage reached a 200 km altitude before reentering the Earth's atmosphere after 300 seconds. The third section of the rocket, containing an atmospheric probe, climbed to 250 km while successfully transmitting scientific data on the atmosphere and the electromagnetic waves on its path back to Earth. It deployed a parachute after six minutes at a lower altitude.\n\nThe second Kavoshgar ([[Kavoshgar-2]]), which carried a space-lab and a restoration system, was launched in November 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.farsnews.net/newstext.php?nn=8709061266|title=Fars News Agency : \u0627\u064a\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u0645\u0648\u0634\u0643 \u0643\u0627\u0648\u0634\u06af\u0631 2 \u0631\u0627 \u0628\u0627 \u0645\u0648\u0641\u0642\u064a\u062a \u0628\u0647 \u0641\u0636\u0627 \u067e\u0631\u062a\u0627\u0628 \u0643\u0631\u062f|publisher=Farsnews.net|accessdate=6 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723130155/http://www.farsnews.net/newstext.php?nn=8709061266 |archive-date=23 July 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Animals in space ===\n{{See also|Monkeys in space}}\n\n* On 3 February 2010, ISA launched a [[Kavoshgar-3]] (Explorer-3) rocket with one rodent, two turtles, and several worms into sub-orbital space and returned them to Earth alive. The rocket was enabled to transfer electronic data and live footage back to Earth. The Iranian Aerospace Organization (IAO) showed live video transmission of mini-environmental lab to enable further studies on the biological capsule.<ref name=\"Iran Fires Satellite Carrier into Space\">{{cite news|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/10/feb/1026.html|title=Iran Fires Satellite Carrier into Space|date=2 February 2010|publisher=payvand.com |accessdate=5 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100208185122/http://www.payvand.com/news/10/feb/1026.html|archive-date=8 February 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> This was the first [[Animals in space|biological]] [[Payload (air and space craft)|payload]] launched by Iran.<ref name=mcuk20100204>{{cite web|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/news/world/811677-animals-are-fired-into-space-in-iranian-rocket |title=Animals are fired into space in Iranian rocket|work=Metro|location=UK|date=4 February 2010|access-date=5 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100413085349/http://www.metro.co.uk/news/world/811677-animals-are-fired-into-space-in-iranian-rocket|archive-date=13 April 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> Iran is the sixth country to send [[animals in space]].\n\n* On 15 March 2011, the ISA launched the [[Kavoshgar-4]] (Explorer-4) rocket carrying a test capsule designed to carry a monkey but without living creatures on board.\n\n* [[Kavoshgar-5]] (Explorer-5) carrying a live monkey was launched for a 20-minute sub-orbital flight in September 2011, however the mission failed. On 3 October 2011, Iran indefinitely postponed further plans while scientists reviewed readiness for future missions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/272624/irans-monkey-does-not-make-it-to-space/|title=Iran's monkey does not make it to space |agency=Agence France-Presse|newspaper=The Express Tribune|date=12 October 2011|accessdate=20 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305042806/http://tribune.com.pk/story/272624/irans-monkey-does-not-make-it-to-space/|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2012, Iran announced that it would send more living creatures into the space by the summer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.farsnews.com/newstext.php?nn%3D9102110289|title=Archived copy|accessdate=4 May 2012|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503105702/http://english.farsnews.com/newstext.php?nn=9102110289|archivedate=3 May 2012}}</ref> Following the last failed attempt, ISA was seeking to successfully send a monkey into space by 2013.<ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/science/2013/01/16/iran-launching-monkey-into-space/ Iran launching monkey into space] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702023236/http://www.foxnews.com/science/2013/01/16/iran-launching-monkey-into-space/|date=2 July 2015}}</ref> ISA head Hamid Fazeli told the Iranian news agency Mehr that the designated monkeys are currently in quarantine.<ref>[http://www.timesofisrael.com/iran-to-launch-a-monkey-into-space/ Times of Israel. Iran to Launch a Monkey into Space] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304060710/http://www.timesofisrael.com/iran-to-launch-a-monkey-into-space/|date=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n* On 29 January 2013, Iranian state media announced that a monkey was sent into space and returned safely aboard the [[Pishgam]] capsule, after having reached a height of 120 km.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dareini |first=Ali|title=Iran Says It Sent Monkey into Space and Back|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/iran-monkey-successfully-space-18333221|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=28 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130131005807/http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/iran-monkey-successfully-space-18333221|archive-date=31 January 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> This was the first time that Iran has sent a [[primate]] into space, 54 years after the first monkeys [[Able and Baker]] returned safely. No details on the timing or location of the launch were given.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.3news.co.nz/Iran-sends-monkey-into-space/tabid/1216/articleID/284734/Default.aspx|work=3 News NZ|title=Iran sends monkey into space|date=29 January 2013|access-date=29 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130213094454/http://www.3news.co.nz/Iran-sends-monkey-into-space/tabid/1216/articleID/284734/Default.aspx|archive-date=13 February 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n* On 14 December 2013, Iran launched a second monkey, named [[Fargam]], on a suborbital flight.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irna.ir/en/News/80950169/Art_&_Culture/Second_monkey_sent_into_space|title=Archived copy|accessdate=11 August 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304103726/http://www.irna.ir/en/News/80950169/Art_%26_Culture/Second_monkey_sent_into_space|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref> The monkey is reported to have been retrieved successfully and safe, after the short 15-minute flight.\n\n== Orbital launches ==\n{{See also|List of orbital launch systems}}\n[[File:Zafar_Satellite.jpg|thumb|Zafar Satellite.]]\n\nOn 17 August 2008, Iran proceeded with the second test launch of a two-stage [[Safir (rocket)|Safir]] SLV from a site south of [[Semnan, Iran|Semnan city]] in the northern part of the [[Dasht-e Kavir|Dasht-e-Kavir desert]]. Reza Taghizadeh, head of the Iranian Aerospace Organization, told state television \"The Safir (Ambassador) satellite carrier was launched today and, for the first time, we successfully launched a dummy satellite into orbit\".\n\nOn 2 February 2009, Iranian state television reported that Iran's first domestically made satellite [[Omid (satellite)|Omid]] ({{lang-fa|\u0627\u0645\u06cc\u062f}}, meaning \"Hope\") had been successfully launched into [[Low Earth orbit]] by a version of Iran's Safir rocket, the [[Safir (rocket)|Safir-2]] and therefore Iran became the 9th country to put a [[Omid (satellite)|domestically built satellite]] into orbit.<ref name=Reuters>{{cite news|title=Iran launches first home-made satellite: state TV|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idUSTRE5120NN20090203|agency=Reuters|date=3 February 2009|accessdate=3 February 2009 |author=Fredrik Dahl and Edmund Blair|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090204204419/http://www.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idUSTRE5120NN20090203|archive-date=4 February 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> The operation was made to coincide with the 30th anniversary of the [[Iranian Revolution]].\n\nIn February 2011, Iranian president [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] announced that there will be many launches of indigenously produced orbiters in 2011\u20132012 period.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gsn.nti.org/gsn/nw_20110207_8612.php|title=Iran Plans Multiple Satellite Launches &#124; NTI|publisher=Gsn.nti.org|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007102011/http://gsn.nti.org/gsn/nw_20110207_8612.php|archive-date=7 October 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIran plans to send one-ton satellites into an orbit of 1000 km and is setting up a new [[Spaceport|launch base]] for this purpose. Iran is also planning to launch satellites into orbits of up to [[Geosynchronous orbit|36,000 km]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://presstv.com/detail/230008.html|title=Archived copy|accessdate=19 March 2012|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303231603/http://presstv.com/detail/230008.html|archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/12/feb/1110.html|title=Archived copy |accessdate=11 February 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140225065920/http://www.payvand.com/news/12/feb/1110.html|archivedate=25 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://presstv.com/detail/225942.html|title=Archived copy|accessdate=11 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303222208/http://presstv.com/detail/225942.html |archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Launched satellites ==\n{{See also|Communications in Iran}}\n\n[[File:Omid 0665.jpg|thumb|[[Omid satellite]]]]\n[[Iran]] is the [[Timeline of first orbital launches by country#List of first orbital launches by country|9th country to put a domestically-built satellite into orbit using its own launcher]] and the sixth to send [[animals in space]].]]\n\n* On 28 October 2005, a [[Kosmos-3M]] booster rocket launched [[Sina-1]]. The joint Iranian Russian Sina-1 project cost US$15 million, and the launch made Iran the 43rd country to possess its own satellite.<ref>{{cite web|last=Alam|first=Ameer|url=http://www.pakalumni.com/profiles/blogs/1119293:BlogPost:64819|title=The Emerging Iranian Space Program \u2013 PakAlumni Worldwide: The Global Social Network |publisher=Pakalumni.com|date=12 April 2009|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316094708/http://www.pakalumni.com/profiles/blogs/1119293:BlogPost:64819|archive-date=16 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n* [[Huanjing (satellite)|Environment 1]], a joint research satellite of [[Iran]], [[China]] and [[Thailand]] was launched on a Chinese [[Long March 2C]] carrier rocket on 6 September 2008, aimed at boosting cooperation on [[natural disaster]]s such as [[flooding]], [[drought]], [[typhoon]], [[landslide]] and [[earthquake]]. The twin [[Earth observation satellite]]s of eight planned were launched from [[Taiyuan Satellite Launch Center|Taiyuan SLC]]. The satellites will work as a constellation with six other satellites yet to be launched. Its observational footprint is 720 km. With a lifespan of more than three years, they have state-of-the-art imaging systems and infrared cameras and provide a global scan every two days. Iran had shouldered US$6.5 million out of the $44 million of the total project cost.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://scitech.people.com.cn/GB/7836524.html|title=\"\u73af\u5883\u51cf\u707e\"A\u3001B\u536b\u661f\u4e00\u7bad\u53cc\u661f\u53d1\u5c04\u6210\u529f|publisher=\u4eba\u6c11\u7f51|date=6 September 2008|accessdate=6 September 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207043054/http://scitech.people.com.cn/GB/7836524.html|archive-date=7 February 2009|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"spacedaily.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.spacedaily.com/news/iran-05d.html|title=Iran, Russia Sign 'Zohreh' Satellite Deal|publisher=Spacedaily.com|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205104231/http://www.spacedaily.com/news/iran-05d.html|archive-date=5 February 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n* [[Omid (satellite)|Omid]], Iran's second satellite, was placed in orbit in February 2009, and was described as a data-processing satellite for research and telecommunications.<ref name=Reuters /><ref>{{cite web|title=Iran puts Omid data-processing satellite into orbit|publisher=[[IRNA]]|url=http://www5.irna.ir/En/View/FullStory/?NewsId=335409&IdLanguage=3|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090206161943/http://www5.irna.ir/En/View/FullStory/?NewsId=335409&IdLanguage=3|url-status=dead|archive-date=6 February 2009|date=3 February 2009|accessdate=3 February 2009}}</ref>\n\n* [[Rasad Satellite|Rasad-1]] is an imaging satellite that has been built and launched successfully by Iran. The satellite was sent into the 260 kilometres orbit by a Safir rocket launcher on 15 June 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sayfa Bulunamad\u0131|language=Turkish|url=http://www.islamidavet.com/english/2010/08/25/iran-to-launch-rasad-1-satellite-in-2011/|accessdate=25 March 2011}}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref name=\"globalsecurity.org\">{{cite web|author=John Pike|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/space/world/iran/irans-second-satellite-launch.htm|title=Iran's Second Satellite Launch |publisher=Globalsecurity.org|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106232622/http://www.globalsecurity.org/space/world/iran/irans-second-satellite-launch.htm|archive-date=6 January 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Hello, Guest|url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/2011/jun/15/iran-launches-homemade-satellite-into-orbit/|title=Iran launches homemade satellite into orbit &#124; UTSanDiego.com|publisher=Signonsandiego.com|date=15 June 2011|accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref> It beams back to earth pictures with 150-meter resolution. It [[orbital decay|decayed from orbit]] three weeks after launch, on 6 July 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zarya.info/Diaries/2011.php|title=2011|work=Zarya Diaries|first=Robert|last=Christy|accessdate=12 July 2011|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019065644/http://www.zarya.info/Diaries/2011.php|archivedate=19 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planet4589.org/space/jsr/latest.html |title=planet4589|work=Jonathan's space Report|first=Jonathan|last=Mcdowell|accessdate=16 July 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718073237/http://planet4589.org/space/jsr/latest.html|archive-date=18 July 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n* [[Navid (satellite)|Navid-e Elm-o Sanat]] (also known as 'Ya Mahdi') which is an \"experimental satellite\" built by students for testing camera and telecommunications equipment was revealed to the public on 3 February 2010. It has store-dump capability and a resolution of 400 meters. On 3 February 2012, Iranian press reported that Iran has successfully launched its domestically-built Navid-e Elm-o Sanat satellite into orbit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail/224596.html|title=PressTV \u2013 Iran successfully launches new satellite into orbit|publisher=Press TV|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205212904/http://www.presstv.ir/detail/224596.html|archive-date=5 February 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The satellite remained in orbit for two months, before [[atmospheric reentry|reentering the atmosphere]] on 1 April 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reentrynews.aero.org/2012005A.html|title=Navis Satellite|work=Recent Reentries|publisher=Center for Orbital and Reentry Debris Studies|accessdate=20 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504010357/http://reentrynews.aero.org/2012005A.html|archive-date=4 May 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n* [[Fajr (satellite)|Fajr]], is an imaging satellite which also carries an experimental locally made GPS system built by [[Iran Electronics Industries]]. The satellite had a life span of 1.5 years and an imaging resolution of 500 meters. It is the first Iranian satellite to use \"cold gas thruster\" and has solar pannels. Originally, it was to be launched in 2012. As were alleged, non-announced by Iran one failed launches of Fajr satellites occurred on 23 May in 2012.<ref name=\"Fajr_failure?\">{{cite journal|last=Hansen|first=Nick|title=Rocket science \u2013 Iran's rocket programme|journal=Jane's Intelligence Review |date=1 October 2012|volume=24|issue=10}}</ref> Finally, Fajr was successfully launched and placed into orbit on 2 February 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.com/Detail/2015/02/02/395807/Iran-places-satellite-into-orbit|title=Archived copy|accessdate=2 February 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160228192939/http://presstv.com/Detail/2015/02/02/395807/Iran-places-satellite-into-orbit|archivedate=28 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxbusiness.com/technology/2015/02/02/state-television-reports-iran-launches-satellite-called-fajr-into-space-amid/|title=Archived copy |accessdate=12 June 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927061418/http://www.foxbusiness.com/technology/2015/02/02/state-television-reports-iran-launches-satellite-called-fajr-into-space-amid/|archivedate=27 September 2015}}</ref> On 26 February 2015, Fajr [[Atmospheric entry|reentered]] earth's atmosphere after 23.8 days in orbit.<ref name=\"Gunter\">{{cite web |url=http://space.skyrocket.de/doc_sdat/fajr.htm|title=Fajr|first=Gunter|last=Krebs|work=Gunter's Space Page|accessdate=27 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212013941/http://space.skyrocket.de/doc_sdat/fajr.htm|archive-date=12 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n* [[Dousti (satellite)|Dousti]], satellite designed for Earth observation. Launched by a Safir rocket in 5 February 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://space.skyrocket.de/doc_sdat/dousti.htm|title=Archived copy |access-date=8 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209180108/https://space.skyrocket.de/doc_sdat/dousti.htm|archive-date=9 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The launch failed.\n\n* [[AUT-SAT]], is a [[Microsatellite (spaceflight)|microsatellite]] being developed by students of [[Amirkabir University of Technology]]. It is designed as a remote sensing satellite with store-dump capability. It was launched on 15 January 2019 by a Simorgh rocket, but failed to reach orbit.<ref name=\"tebyan.net\"/><ref name=\"ayenehnashriat.com\"/> Amir Kabir satellite, weighing 80 kg, will reportedly be placed in a sun-synchronous orbit of 660 km in radius, and will remain in space between three and five years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.com/detail/2012/07/22/252215/iran-aims-to-launch-another-satellite/|title=Archived copy|accessdate=24 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303210527/http://www.presstv.com/detail/2012/07/22/252215/iran-aims-to-launch-another-satellite/|archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref> The launcher is expected to be a Simorgh missile.<ref name=\"english.farsnews.com\"/>\n\n* On 9 February 2020, Iran successfully launched the [[communication satellite]], Zafar 1, through a [[Simorgh (rocket)|Simorgh]] rocket from [[Imam Khomeini Spaceport|Imam Khomeini Space Center]] at 19:15 local time. However, spokesman for the [[Ministry of Defence and Armed Forces Logistics (Iran)|defence ministry]]'s space programme, Ahmad Hosseini, notified that the satellite didn't reach the required speed in its final moments for being put in the [[orbit]].<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.spacewar.com/reports/Iran_satellite_launch_fails_in_blow_to_space_programme_999.html|title=Iran satellite launch fails, in blow to space program|accessdate=9 February 2020|website=Space War}}</ref>\n\n* On 22 April 2020, Iran successfully launched a military satellite into a 426 x 444 km orbit.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.space.com/iran-launches-first-military-satellite.html|title=Iran launches its 1st military satellite into orbit: reports|accessdate=22 April 2020|website=Space.com}}</ref>\n\n== Unlaunched satellites ==\n* [[Nahid (satellite)|Nahid]] (1), satellite with folding solar panels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.farsnews.com/newstext.php?nn%3D13910213000402|title=Archived copy|accessdate=15 May 2012|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304002859/http://www.farsnews.com/newstext.php?nn=13910213000402|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/news/313410-Russia-Iran-space-cooperation/|title=Archived copy|accessdate=1 December 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201080642/https://www.rt.com/news/313410-Russia-Iran-space-cooperation/ |archivedate=1 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n* [[Toloo (satellite)|Toloo]], is the first of a new generation of [[reconnaissance satellite]]s being built by [[Iran Electronics Industries]] with [[SIGINT]] capabilities.<ref name=\"payvand.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/11/nov/1025.html|title=Iran to Launch Toloo Satellite Next Year|publisher=Payvand.com|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111217073304/http://www.payvand.com/news/11/nov/1025.html|archive-date=17 December 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> It will be launched by a [[Simorgh]].<ref name=\"english.farsnews.com\">{{cite web|url=http://english.farsnews.com/newstext.aspx?nn%3D13931113001060|title=Archived copy|accessdate=3 February 2015|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150709031827/http://english.farsnews.com/newstext.aspx?nn=13931113001060|archivedate=9 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n* [[Nasir 1 (satellite)|Nasir 1]], Iran's indigenously designed [[satellite navigation system]] (SAT NAV) has been manufactured to find the precise locations of satellites moving in orbit.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/middle-east/report-iran-unveils-self-made-satellite-navigation-system-1.433673|title=Archived copy|accessdate=3 June 2012|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716041438/http://www.haaretz.com/news/middle-east/report-iran-unveils-self-made-satellite-navigation-system-1.433673|archivedate=16 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.payvand.com/news/12/may/1309.html|title=Archived copy|accessdate=19 January 2013|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618140138/http://www.payvand.com/news/12/may/1309.html|archivedate=18 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n* [[Sharif (satellite)|Sharif]] satellite was originally scheduled for launch in 2012 is an observation satellite with an imaging resolution of better than 12.5 meters. The satellite is manufactured by [[Sharif University of Technology]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://isna.ir/fa/news/91021307234/%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%8A%D8%B3-%D8%B3%D8%A7%D8%B2%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%86-%D9%81%D8%B6%D8%A7%D9%8A%D9%8A-%D8%AE%D8%A8%D8%B1-%D8%AF%D8%A7%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D8%B9%D8%B2%D8%A7%D9%85-%D9%85%D9%88%D8%AC%D9%88%D8%AF-%D8%B2%D9%86%D8%AF%D9%87|title=Archived copy|accessdate=15 May 2012|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304111829/http://isna.ir/fa/news/91021307234/%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%8A%D8%B3-%D8%B3%D8%A7%D8%B2%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%86-%D9%81%D8%B6%D8%A7%D9%8A%D9%8A-%D8%AE%D8%A8%D8%B1-%D8%AF%D8%A7%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D8%B9%D8%B2%D8%A7%D9%85-%D9%85%D9%88%D8%AC%D9%88%D8%AF-%D8%B2%D9%86%D8%AF%D9%87|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n* [[Zafar-1]], is an imaging satellite to be launched in 2012 and will have a resolution better than 80 meters.<ref name=\"tebyan.net\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tebyan.net/index.aspx?pid=17257&threadID=280555 |title=\u0631\u0648\u0646\u0645\u0627\u06cc\u06cc \u0627\u0632 4 \u0645\u0627\u0647\u0648\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u0628\u0648\u0645\u06cc\u060c\u200c \u0645\u0648\u062a\u0648\u0631 \u0645\u0627\u0647\u0648\u0627\u0631\u0647\u200c\u0628\u0631 \"\u0633\u0641\u06cc\u0631B1 \" \u0648 \"\u0643\u0627\u0648\u0634\u06af\u06314 \"|publisher=Tebyan.net|accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://presstv.com/detail/224597.htm|title=No Operation |publisher=Presstv.com|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115165554/http://presstv.com/detail/224597.htm|archive-date=15 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"ayenehnashriat.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ayenehnashriat.com/Pages/News-2661.html|title=Archived copy|accessdate=25 March 2011|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110904200632/http://www.ayenehnashriat.com/Pages/News-2661.html|archivedate=4 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mehrnews.com/fa/newsdetail.aspx?NewsID=1252012|title=Iran, world, political, sport, economic news and headlines|publisher=MehrNews.com|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714070510/http://www.mehrnews.com/fa/newsdetail.aspx?NewsID=1252012|archive-date=14 July 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> The satellite will be sent into a [[geostationary orbit]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail/2014/01/06/344130/iran-developing-zafar-sat-space-model/|title=Archived copy|accessdate=30 January 2014|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701200924/http://www.presstv.ir/detail/2014/01/06/344130/iran-developing-zafar-sat-space-model/|archivedate=1 July 2015}}</ref> The launcher is expected to be a Simorgh missile.<ref name=\"english.farsnews.com\"/>\n\n* [[Mesbah]] (meaning 'Lantern') was to be built by Iran in collaboration with Italy's [http://www.cgspace.it/ Carlo Gavazzi Space S.p.A]. Mesbah was a [[Low Earth orbit]] [[telecommunication satellite]]. The satellite was never launched as both Russia and Italy refused to cooperate with Iran anymore on space projects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://presstv.com/detail/173346.html|title=Iran to retrieve Mesbah-1 sat from Italy|publisher=Press TV|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316190052/http://www.presstv.com/detail/173346.html|archive-date=16 March 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The original Mesbah project was later on replaced by indigenous [[Mesbah-2]] which is to be built and launched by Iran alone.<ref name=\"chinadaily.com.cn\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/world/2009-11/21/content_9015504.htm |title=Iran to launch satellite on its own by late 2011|work=China Daily|date=21 November 2009|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110125235234/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/world/2009-11/21/content_9015504.htm|archive-date=25 January 2011|url-status=live }}</ref> It was reported, in April 2011, that the US$10 million satellite built in Italy, has not been delivered to Iran. Italy has refused to hand over the satellite to Iran under the pretext of [[Sanctions against Iran|international sanctions on Iran]]. Iran maintains that the satellite be handed over for its launch by an Iranian satellite carrier.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zawya.com/story.cfm/sidANA20110405T123153ZFWD18|title=Zawya|publisher=Zawya |accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=BaniComm Co.|url=http://www.isna.ir/ISNA/NewsView.aspx?ID=News-1741444&Lang=E|title=ISNA \u2013 04-05-2011 \u2013 90/1/16 \u2013 Service: / Science / News ID: 1741444 |publisher=Isna.ir|accessdate=6 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120802170921/http://www.isna.ir/ISNA/NewsView.aspx?ID=News-1741444&Lang=E|archivedate=2 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.trend.az/regions/iran/1856293.html|title=Iranian official: Italy deviates from handing over Misbah satellite \u2013 Trend|publisher=En.trend.az|date=5 April 2011|accessdate=6 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903072346/http://en.trend.az/regions/iran/1856293.html|archive-date=3 September 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n* [[Mesbah-2]] is a limited application communication satellite which was conceived as a locally designed satellite after the original [[Mesbah]] project failed to materialize due to international pressures on Iran. It will have a life span of 3 years with store dump capability and its own navigation system. It is scheduled for launch in 2012.<ref name=\"globalsecurity.org\"/><ref name=\"google.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jCDd1NvNvsNUIU4Us1P-aYbvT9HA|title=AFP: Iran to unveil three new home-built satellites: report|publisher=Google|date=20 January 2010|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429164444/http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jCDd1NvNvsNUIU4Us1P-aYbvT9HA|archive-date=29 April 2011|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"payvand.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/10/feb/1025.html|title=Iran unveils three new home-made satellites|publisher=Payvand.com|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316232028/http://www.payvand.com/news/10/feb/1025.html|archive-date=16 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"chinadaily.com.cn\"/>\n\n* [[Qaem (satellite)|Qaem]], is a [[geosynchronous satellite|geosynchronous communication satellite]] that is being developed by Iran and is scheduled to be launched on an Iranian carrier by 2016. The satellite is going to have a life expectancy of 15 years, broadcasting TV and Radio channels.<ref name=\"isa.ir\">{{cite web|author=Sina Shafigh|url=http://www.isa.ir/components1.php?rQV==wHQxAkOklUZnFWdn5WYMJXZ0VWbhJXYw9lZ8BkN1QDQ6QWStVGdp9lZ8BUM4ATMApDZJ52bpR3Yh9lZ|title=\u0633\u0627\u0632\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0641\u0636\u0627\u06cc\u06cc \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646|publisher=Isa.ir|accessdate=6 February 2012|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421104347/http://www.isa.ir/components1.php?rQV==wHQxAkOklUZnFWdn5WYMJXZ0VWbhJXYw9lZ8BkN1QDQ6QWStVGdp9lZ8BUM4ATMApDZJ52bpR3Yh9lZ|archivedate=21 April 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"sri.ac.ir\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sri.ac.ir/index.aspx?siteid=1&pageid=141&newsview=19|title=\u0633\u0627\u064a\u062a \u0627\u0635\u0644\u064a - \u0627\u062e\u0628\u0627\u0631\u0648 \u0631\u0648\u064a\u062f\u0627\u062f\u0647\u0627|publisher=Sri.ac.ir|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316094724/http://www.sri.ac.ir/index.aspx?siteid=1&pageid=141&newsview=19|archive-date=16 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n* [[Pars Sepehr]], is a remote sensing satellite being built and to be launched from Iran. Its launch date is not yet confirmed.<ref name=\"isa.ir\"/><ref name=\"sri.ac.ir\"/>\n\n* [[Pars-2]], is a remote sensing satellite being built and to be launched from Iran. Its launch schedule has not yet been announced.<ref name=\"isa.ir\"/><ref name=\"sri.ac.ir\"/>\n\n* [[ZS4]] is an Iranian satellite to be launched by an Iranian launcher. Its mission role and launch date have not been revealed.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Book: ''Iran: Development \u2013 space launch systems and satellites'', By: Brian Harvey, Henk H. F. Smid and Th\u00e9o Pirard.</ref><ref name=\"spatialsource.com.au\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spatialsource.com.au/article/Irans-Space-Ambitions/ZETSPMAZSF.html?page%3D3 |title=Archived copy|accessdate=21 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110306002712/http://www.spatialsource.com.au/article/Irans-Space-Ambitions/ZETSPMAZSF.html?page=3 |archivedate=6 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://parviztarikhi.files.wordpress.com/2010/02/heading2space.pdf|title=Archived copy|accessdate=21 May 2012|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315153403/https://parviztarikhi.files.wordpress.com/2010/02/heading2space.pdf|archivedate=15 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n* [[Sina-2]] is a small satellite that will replace the mission role of [[Sina-1]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref name=\"spatialsource.com.au\"/>\n\n* [[SM2S]] is an Iranian satellite to be launched by an Iranian launcher. Its mission role and launch date have not been revealed.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref>http://iran.ru/eng/iran_news.php?act=news_by_id&news_id=20655{{dead link|date=December 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref>\n\n* Iran is also to implement 10 satellite projects with [[Asia-Pacific Space Cooperation Organization]] (APSCO) members. The organization has defined 10 projects on designing, building and launching light satellites, middle class satellites weighing 500\u2013600 kg, research satellites, remote-sensing and telecommunications satellites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/10/oct/1160.html|title=Iran to implement 10 satellite projects with APSCO members|publisher=Payvand.com |accessdate=6 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120812210104/http://www.payvand.com/news/10/oct/1160.html |archive-date=12 August 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/11/apr/1022.html|title=Iran plans to join APSCO satellite-building project|publisher=Payvand.com|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120904233927/http://www.payvand.com/news/11/apr/1022.html|archive-date=4 September 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n* [[Besharat (satellite)|Besharat]] satellite is being built by Iran with collaboration of some [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation|OIC]] members which have volunteered in the project. It is to be launched by Iran. The countries which are jointly working with Iran on the project are Pakistan, Turkey, Malaysia and some Arab countries. Its launch date is not yet confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|author=John Pike |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/space/world/iran/safir-1-2.htm|title=Iran Space Launch Vehicles|publisher=Globalsecurity.org|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104090533/http://www.globalsecurity.org/space/world/iran/safir-1-2.htm|archive-date=4 November 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.payvand.com/news/08/aug/1223.html|title=Iran, OIC to build satellite 'Besharat'|publisher=Payvand.com|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120904233933/http://www.payvand.com/news/08/aug/1223.html|archive-date=4 September 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iran-daily.com/1384/2408/html/economy.htm|title=Internet Archive Wayback Machine|publisher=Web.archive.org|date=10 December 2007|accessdate=6 February 2012|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207115701/http://www.iran-daily.com/1384/2408/html/economy.htm|archivedate=7 February 2009}}</ref>\n\n* [[Saar (satellite)|Saar (Starling)]] will be produced by Iran's [[K.N.Toosi University of Technology|Khajeh Nasir Toosi University of Technology]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.presstv.com/detail/2012/07/30/253468/iran-to-build-new-indigenous-satellite/|title=Archived copy|accessdate=1 August 2012|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120801033928/http://www.presstv.com/detail/2012/07/30/253468/iran-to-build-new-indigenous-satellite/|archivedate=1 August 2012}}</ref> No further details have been given.\n\n* [[Zohreh]], is a [[geosynchronous satellite|geosynchronous communication satellite]] which was originally proposed before the Revolution in the 1970s as part of a joint Indian-Iranian project of four Iranian satellites to be launched by the then upcoming [[NASA]] [[space shuttle]]s. Iran had also negotiated with France to build and launch the satellites but the project never materialized. In 2005, Iran negotiated with Russia to build and launch the first Zohreh satellite under an agreement worth $132 million with the satellite launch date stipulated as 2007\u20132008. The new agreement had followed the earlier failed negotiations with Russia in 2003 when Russia cancelled the project under US pressures. The satellite was to be of [[Ekspress|Express-1000]] type and capable of relaying telephone, fax, data and television signals with a life span of 15 years.<ref name=\"spacedaily.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inss.org.il/publications.php?cat=21&incat=&read=160&print=1|title=The Institute for National Security Studies |publisher=INSS|date=27 October 2005|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326084549/http://www.inss.org.il/publications.php?cat=21&incat=&read=160&print=1|archive-date=26 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=John Pike|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/space/world/iran/zohreh.htm|title=Zohreh|publisher=Globalsecurity.org|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207110332/http://www.globalsecurity.org/space/world/iran/zohreh.htm|archive-date=7 February 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2010, Iran announced that it will build and launch the satellite locally as the foreign contractors had refused to complete the project. New launch date for the satellite was announced as 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peymane.ir/fa/pages/?cid=25045|title=\u0645\u0627\u0647\u0648\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u0632\u0647\u0631\u0647 \u062a\u0627 \u0686\u0647\u0627\u0631\u0633\u0627\u0644 \u0622\u064a\u0646\u062f\u0647 \u0628\u0647 \u0641\u0636\u0627 \u067e\u0631\u062a\u0627\u0628 \u0645\u064a \u0634\u0648\u062f|publisher=Peymane.ir|accessdate=6 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316094724/http://www.peymane.ir/fa/pages/?cid=25045|archivedate=16 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Behnegarsoft.com|url=http://alef.ir/1388/content/view/84900/|title=\u0627\u0644\u0641 - \u067e\u0631\u062a\u0627\u0628 \u0645\u0627\u0647\u0648\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u0632\u0647\u0631\u0647 \u062a\u0627 4 \u0633\u0627\u0644 \u0622\u064a\u0646\u062f\u0647|publisher=Alef.ir|accessdate=6 February 2012 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005181956/http://alef.ir/1388/content/view/84900/|archivedate=5 October 2011}}</ref> Russia had announced in 2009 that it is not going to cooperate with Iran on any space projects but reversed course again following the lifting of international [[sanctions against Iran]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last=Weinberger|first=Sharon |url=https://www.wired.com/dangerroom/2009/06/russians-say-nyet-to-another-iranian-satellite/|title=Russians Say 'Nyet' To Another Iranian Satellite &#124; Danger Room|work=Wired|date=25 June 2009|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120115041637/http://www.wired.com/dangerroom/2009/06/russians-say-nyet-to-another-iranian-satellite|archive-date=15 January 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allourmight.com/?p=674|title=Blog Archive \u00bb Iran/Russia and arms sales, pre-Obama visit|publisher=All Our Might|date=26 June 2009|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325222755/http://www.allourmight.com/?p=674|archive-date=25 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azernews.az/region/106464.html|title=Archived copy|accessdate=14 December 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161229110433/http://www.azernews.az/region/106464.html|archivedate=29 December 2016}}</ref> Iran has also solicited [[NASA]]'s cooperation in future space projects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/irans-space-agency-eyes-cooperation-with-nasa/|title=Archived copy|accessdate=4 December 2016|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221011036/http://www.timesofisrael.com/irans-space-agency-eyes-cooperation-with-nasa/|archivedate=21 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Space centers ==\n{{Main|Imam Khomeini Spaceport}}\n{{See also|List of space agencies|List of rocket launch sites}}\n{{kml}}\n\nThe main launch site of the [[Iranian Space Agency]] is [[Shahrud, Iran|Shahrud]], located at {{Coord|36|25|0|N|55|01|0|E|name=Iranian Space Agency Emamshahr|type:landmark_region:IR_scale:10000}}, where suborbital [[Shahab 3]]s LV have been launched.\n\n[[Qom]], located at {{Coord|34|39|0|N|50|54|0|E|name=Iranian Space Agency Qom|type:landmark_region:IR_scale:10000}}, is the other launch site.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/iran-builds-space-center-launch-satellites-125730061.html;_ylt=A2KJjagamcpPhiYAag3QtDMD|title=Archived copy|accessdate=3 June 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305081945/http://news.yahoo.com/iran-builds-space-center-launch-satellites-125730061.html%3B_ylt%3DA2KJjagamcpPhiYAag3QtDMD|archivedate=5 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn occasion of the inaugural launch of Iran's first [[Safir (rocket)|Safir-class]] sub-orbital rocket called [[Kavoshgar-1]] (Explorer-1), Iran unveiled on 4 February 2008, its first Satellite Launch Center {{Coord|35.234|N|53.921|E|name=Iranian Space Agency Satellite Launch Center Semnan|type:landmark_region:IR_scale:10000}} in [[Semnan, Iran|Semnan city]]. The facility includes an underground command and control center, a tracking station and a launchpad among other structures.\n\nIn December 2010, it was announced that due to geographical limitations of first space center in injecting satellite into orbit, studies have been carried out for setting up a second (satellite) launch pad.<ref name=\"presstv.ir\">{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail/155116.html|title=No Operation|publisher=Press TV|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011172937/http://www.presstv.ir/detail/155116.html|archive-date=11 October 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The new national [[spaceport]] of Iran, named after [[Imam Khomeini]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/12/jun/1015.html|title=Archived copy|accessdate=3 June 2012|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304204457/http://www.payvand.com/news/12/jun/1015.html|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref> is being built in Semnan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7oSVX6mkmds|title=Archived copy|accessdate=24 January 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161207040605/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7oSVX6mkmds|archivedate=7 December 2016}}</ref> \n\nThis new port is to be used to launch all future Iranian space missions similar to American [[Kennedy Space Center]] or the [[Baikonur Cosmodrome]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mashreghnews.ir/NSite/FullStory/News/?Id=34283|title=\u062a\u0627\u0633\u064a\u0633 \u067e\u0627\u064a\u06af\u0627\u0647 \u0645\u0644\u064a \u067e\u0631\u062a\u0627\u0628 \u0645\u0627\u0647\u0648\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u062f\u0631\u062c\u0646\u0648\u0628 \u0634\u0631\u0642 \u06a9\u0634\u0648\u0631 - \u0645\u0634\u0631\u0642 \u0646\u06cc\u0648\u0632|publisher=mashreghnews.ir|date=15 June 2011|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320152924/http://www.mashreghnews.ir/NSite/FullStory/News/?Id=34283|archive-date=20 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>http://baztab.jetjoin.com/2011/03/11/%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%B3%DB%8C%D8%B3-%D9%BE%D8%A7%DB%8C%DA%AF%D8%A7%D9%87-%D9%85%D9%84%DB%8C-%D9%BE%D8%B1%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%A8-%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%87%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%87-%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%AC%D9%86%D9%88%D8%A8/{{dead link|date=December 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ihrc.ir/FA/NewsShow.aspx?ID=8141|title=\u0627\u062e\u062a\u0635\u0627\u0635 \u06f4 \u0645\u064a\u0644\u064a\u0627\u0631\u062f \u062a\u0648\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0639\u062a\u0628\u0627\u0631 \u0628\u0631\u0627\u064a \u0633\u0627\u062e\u062a \u0627\u0628\u0631\u0631\u0627\u064a\u0627\u0646\u0647 \u0645\u0644\u064a|publisher=Ihrc.ir|accessdate=6 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110818084219/http://ihrc.ir/FA/NewsShow.aspx?ID=8141|archivedate=18 August 2011}}</ref> In March 2011, [[Jane's Information Group]] reported on the basis of its satellite imagery analysis of Iranian space launch sites that Iran is aggressively building complex facilities with very rapid pace showing the nation's inclinations towards space readiness.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.janes.com/articles/Janes-Defence-Weekly-2011/Iran-accelerates-space-and-missile-launch-projects.html|title=Iran accelerates space and missile launch projects \u2013 Jane's Defence Weekly|publisher=Articles.janes.com|date=18 March 2011|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503102555/http://articles.janes.com/articles/Janes-Defence-Weekly-2011/Iran-accelerates-space-and-missile-launch-projects.html|archive-date=3 May 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2013, Iran inaugurated its first space monitoring center located near Delijan in Markazi province, according to Iran's Defense Minister General Ahmad Vahidi the new center which was named Imam Ja'far Sadeq would mostly be used to track and detect space objects and satellites passing overhead using radar, electro-optic and radio systems.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.farsnews.com/newstext.php?nn%3D9203180420|title=Archived copy|accessdate=9 June 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130613054423/http://english.farsnews.com/newstext.php?nn=9203180420|archivedate=13 June 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.farsnews.com/imgrep.php?nn%3D13920319000829|title=Archived copy|accessdate=9 June 2013|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304045552/http://www.farsnews.com/imgrep.php?nn=13920319000829|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rt.com/news/iran-space-monitoring-center-429/|title=Archived copy|accessdate=9 June 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160526185603/https://www.rt.com/news/iran-space-monitoring-center-429/|archivedate=26 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Space test laboratory ==\n{{See also|Iranian Space Research Center|Science and technology in Iran}}\n\nIn 2011, Iran launched a number of laboratories for testing \"space structures and systems\" in line with its progressing space program. The laboratory includes ten labs to \"reinforce infrastructures of Iran's space industry\" and help improve the abilities of human resources.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail/162692.html|title=Archived copy|accessdate=15 March 2011|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011173023/http://www.presstv.ir/detail/162692.html|archivedate=11 October 2012}}</ref>{{clarify|date=February 2012|reason=source is too vague \u2013 what does it mean by \"laboratories\" and \"launch\"? Please clarify and reword this to serve an encyclopedia purpose}}\n\n== Manned space program ==\n{{Main|Iranian manned spaceship project}}\n\nIran expressed for the first time its intention to send a human to space during the summit of Soviet and Iranian Presidents at 21 June 1990. [[President of the Soviet Union|Soviet President]] [[Mikhail Gorbachev]] reached an agreement in principle with then-President [[Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani]] to make joint Soviet-Iranian manned flights to [[Mir space station]] but this agreement was never realized after the breakup of the [[Soviet Union]].\n\nAlmost two decades later the [[IRNA|Iranian News Agency]] claimed on 21 November 2005, that the Iranians have a manned space program along with plans for the development of a spacecraft and a space laboratory. <!--do not delete! Chinese IRNA link when first accessed<ref>[http://www.irna.ir/ch/news/view/menu-332/0511213283154918.html]</ref>--><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSBLA13323720080821 |title=Iran plans manned space mission in 10 years|agency=Reuters|date=21 August 2008|accessdate=6 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722041036/http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSBLA13323720080821|archive-date=22 July 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Iran Aerospace Industries Organization]] (IAIO) head Reza Taghipour on 20 August 2008, revealed Iran intends to launch a manned mission into space within a decade. This goal was described as the country's top priority for the next 10 years, in order to make Iran the leading space power of the region by 2021.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3585540,00.html|title=First Iranian in space within decade|publisher=[[Ynetnews]]|date=20 August 2008|accessdate=20 August 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080824010221/http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3585540,00.html|archive-date=24 August 2008|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.rian.ru/world/20080820/116164664.html|title=Iran to send first astronaut into space within 10 years|agency=RIA Novosti|date=20 August 2008|accessdate=11 September 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080909235859/http://en.rian.ru/world/20080820/116164664.html|archive-date=9 September 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2010, President Ahmadinejad announced that Iran's first astronaut should be sent into space on board an Iranian spacecraft by no later than 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-10747390|work=BBC News|title=Iran aims to send man into space by 2019|date=23 July 2010|access-date=21 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125130121/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-10747390|archive-date=25 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.com/detail.aspx?id%3D135966%26sectionid%3D351020101|title=Archived copy|accessdate=23 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304003240/http://www.presstv.com/detail.aspx?id=135966&sectionid=351020101|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref> Later on in December 2010, Iranian Communications and Information Technology Minister [[Reza Taghipour]] stated that \"The initial steps for the plan have been taken, and the study phase on the definition of subsystems, sub-projects, costs, and what projects need to be developed toward that end, has been conducted, which needs to be submitted to the Supreme Council on Space\".<ref name=\"presstv.ir\"/> According to Iranian manned space program, the first [[sub-orbital spaceflight]] was take place by 2016 at an altitude below 200 kilometers as preparation for the eventual [[orbital spaceflight]].<ref name=ISA-suborbit>{{cite web|url=http://www.isa.ir/components1.php?rQV==wHQyAkOklUZnFWdn5WYMJXZ0VWbhJXYw9lZ8B0N3QDQ6QWStVGdp9lZ8BUM4ATMApDZJ52bpR3Yh9lZ |title=Dispatching Iranian astronaut to below 200 km orbit|publisher=Iranian Space Agency|date=31 May 2011|accessdate=29 December 2012|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224101258/http://www.isa.ir/components1.php?rQV==wHQyAkOklUZnFWdn5WYMJXZ0VWbhJXYw9lZ8B0N3QDQ6QWStVGdp9lZ8BUM4ATMApDZJ52bpR3Yh9lZ|archivedate=24 December 2013}}</ref> No such vehicle was developed.\n\nOn 17 February 2015, Iran unveiled a mock [[prototype]] of [[Iranian manned spaceship project|Iranian manned spaceship]] that would capable of taking astronauts into space.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.payvand.com/news/15/feb/1087.html|title=Archived copy|accessdate=22 February 2015|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304204646/http://www.payvand.com/news/15/feb/1087.html|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref> According to Iran's Space Administrator, this program was put on hold in 2017 indefinitely.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/31/world/middleeast/iran-space.html|title=Iran Drops Plan to Send Human into Space, Citing Cost|last=GLADSTONE|first=RICK|access-date=1 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170601065046/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/31/world/middleeast/iran-space.html|archive-date=1 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Space station ===\nAccording to unofficial Chinese internet sources, an Iranian participation in the future [[Chinese space program#Space station|Chinese space station]] program has been discussed. This involvement might range from simply sending astronauts to the 60 tons class space station to contributing with development of a space laboratory module. International manned space cooperation has officially been disclosed for the first time after the launch of the Chinese [[Shenzhou 7]] spacecraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/newscenter/2008-09/26/content_10114727.htm|title=\u6743\u5a01\u53d1\u5e03:\u795e\u821f\u98de\u8239\u5c06\u4ece\u795e\u516b\u5f00\u59cb\u6279\u91cf\u751f\u4ea7|publisher=\u65b0\u534e\u7f51|date=26 September 2008|accessdate=26 September 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080929025036/http://news.xinhuanet.com/newscenter/2008-09/26/content_10114727.htm|archivedate=29 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n=== Lunar program ===\nWestern media has quoted that Iran has plans to land an astronaut on the Moon by 2025. Currently Iran doesn't have a medium lift rocket, therefore as of now Iran sending a human to space is unlikely due to the lack of equipment.<ref name=ISA-suborbit/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ieet.org/index.php/IEET/more/nicholas20120405|title=Archived copy|accessdate=5 April 2012|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160908095840/http://ieet.org/index.php/IEET/more/nicholas20120405|archivedate=8 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.space.com/13270-iran-space-monkey-launch-failure.html|title=Archived copy|accessdate=8 September 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224030624/http://www.space.com/13270-iran-space-monkey-launch-failure.html |archivedate=24 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn22136-iran-space-agency-to-launch-a-monkey-into-space.html|title=Iran Space Agency to launch a monkey into space \u2013 space \u2013 03 August 2012 \u2013 New Scientist|accessdate=7 September 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701195840/http://www.newscientist.com/article/dn22136-iran-space-agency-to-launch-a-monkey-into-space.html|archivedate=1 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=Harding>{{cite book|last=Harding|first=Robert C.|title=Space Policy in Developing Countries: The Search for Security and Development on the Final Frontier|date=2012|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-53845-9|page=131}}</ref><ref name=Lele>{{cite book|last=Lele|first=Ajey|title=Asian Space Race: Rhetoric or Reality?|date=2012|publisher=Springer |isbn=978-8132207320|edition=2013|page=33}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\n{{See also|Nuclear program of Iran}}\n\nThe Iranian space program has been condemned by United States and Europe because of their concern over its military potential. Some analysts have compared the relatively fast Iranian advancement in space technology to Russia's [[Sputnik program]] with the prediction that this advancement will propel Iran's military capability in other areas as well. The military concerns over Iran's space program has been exacerbated over Safir rocket's advanced 2nd stage which Iran has kept secret by not releasing any technical information related to the second stage of the rocket, keeping outside observers guessing over the technicalities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://meria.idc.ac.il/journal/2006/issue3/jv10no3a2.html|title=Iran's Space Program: The Next Genie in a Bottle?|publisher=Meria.idc.ac.il|accessdate=6 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111227052716/http://meria.idc.ac.il/journal/2006/issue3/jv10no3a2.html|archivedate=27 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://biak-spaceport.blogspot.com/2010/02/emerging-iranian-space-program.html|title=Biak Spaceport: The Emerging Iranian Space Program|publisher=Biak-spaceport.blogspot.com|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316094747/http://biak-spaceport.blogspot.com/2010/02/emerging-iranian-space-program.html|archive-date=16 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=3934643{{dead link|date=December 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spacewar.com/reports/Iranian_missiles_have_worldwide_reach_Russia_999.html|title=Iranian missiles have 'worldwide reach': Russia|publisher=Spacewar.com|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207120524/http://www.spacewar.com/reports/Iranian_missiles_have_worldwide_reach_Russia_999.html|archive-date=7 February 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/02/03/world/main4771491.shtml?source=RSSattr=HOME_4771491|publisher=CBS News|title=Iran Launches First Homegrown Satellite|date=3 February 2009|access-date=30 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214055515/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/02/03/world/main4771491.shtml?source=RSSattr=HOME_4771491|archive-date=14 February 2009|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.asemangasht.com/travel_news/show.php?id=24|title=Travel News \u2013 Iran claims first launch of its own satellite|publisher=Asemangasht.com|accessdate=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317012937/http://www.asemangasht.com/travel_news/show.php?id=24|archive-date=17 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/iran/2575063/Iran-launches-rocket-capable-of-carrying-satellite.html|location=London|work=The Daily Telegraph|first=Our|last=Foreign|title=Iran launches rocket capable of carrying satellite|date=17 August 2008|access-date=5 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907182945/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/iran/2575063/Iran-launches-rocket-capable-of-carrying-satellite.html|archive-date=7 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> For Radio Free Europe, independent experts interviewed disagreed with assertion made by the U.S. and various European countries. [[Stockholm International Peace Research Institute|SIPRI's]] Tytti Er\u00e4st\u00f6 stated space launch vehicle program can contribute to missile development yet it isn't a shortcut for development of long range missiles such as intercontinental ballistic missiles, historically the ICBMs were converted to SLVs and never was in history SLV converted to ICBM. [[International Institute for Strategic Studies|IISS]] Michael Elleman stated that claims made by the U.S. such as [[Mike Pompeo]] are grossly exaggerating contribution of SLV program to ICBM program and that it is misguided to suggest that SLV program is cover for nuclear capable ICBMs as claims made are a political statement. ST Analytics Markus Schiller stated that there is no indication that Iran is trying to develop missiles with range longer than 2000 km as Iran has been working on improving accuracy of their existing short and medium range missiles.<ref>https://www.rferl.org/a/is-iran-converting-space-launchers-into-long-range-missiles-/30437113.html</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Iran|Science|Spaceflight}}\n\n* [[Aerospace Force of the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]]\n* [[Anousheh Ansari]] \u2013 First [[Iranian-American]] cosmonaut\n* [[Colonization of Mars]]\n* [[Colonization of the Moon]]\n* [[Economy of Iran]]\n* [[International rankings of Iran#Science and technology|International rankings of Iran in science and technology]]\n* [[Iran Aviation Industries Organization]]\n* [[Timeline of first orbital launches by country#List of first orbital launches by country|List of first orbital launches by country]]\n* [[List of government space agencies]]\n* [[List of Iranian research centers]]\n* [[List of missions to the Moon]]\n* [[Human spaceflight#National spacefaring attempts|National spacefaring programs]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.isa.ir/ Iranian Space Agency]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070418150218/http://www.spacescience.ir/ Space Science]\n* [http://www.globalsecurity.org/space/world/iran/agency.htm Iranian Space Agencies (listing)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110406115504/http://www.astronautix.com/country/iran.htm Iran space program]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060615142503/http://astronautix.com/lvs/shaabslv.htm Shahab SLV]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090216100124/http://aio.ir/ Aerospace Industries Organization]\n* [http://www.globalsecurity.org/space/world/iran/index.html Iran in Space] Globalsecurity.org\n\n;Videos\n* [http://presstv.com/Detail/2016/11/16/493845/Iran-aerospace-achievements A glimpse of Iran\u2019s latest aerospace achievements] \u2013 [[PressTV]] (2016)\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7oSVX6mkmds Imam Khomeini Space Center \u2013 Iran] \u2013 [[Nuclear Threat Initiative]] (2013)\n* {{YouTube|8OKu04fYgTk|Video on Iran Space Program}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/PressTVGlobalNews#p/u/8/JPKzGVGUVPw Iran's space technology program \u2013 Part I] [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ac8JPUXx640 Part II] [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E2FF0Cvb7J8 Part III] \u2013 [[PressTV]]\n\n{{Iranian Space Program}}\n{{Public sector space agencies}}\n{{Space exploration lists and timelines}}\n\n[[Category:Space program of Iran]]\n[[Category:Government agencies of Iran]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 2003]]\n[[Category:2003 establishments in Iran]]\n[[Category:Science and technology in Iran]]\n[[Category:Scientific organisations based in Iran]]\n[[Category:Space agencies]]\n", "name_user": "1775sd", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added name and orbit type to 22 April 2020 successful satellite launch", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iranian_Space_Agency"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Republic of Ireland", "text_new": "{{About|the coronavirus pandemic in the Republic of Ireland|the pandemic in Northern Ireland|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Northern Ireland}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Ireland}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ireland\n| map1            = Confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Ireland by county.webm\n| legend1         = Confirmed cases by [[Counties of Ireland|county]]\n| alt1            = \n| map2            = Confirmed cases of COVID-19 per 100k inhabitants in Ireland.webm\n| legend2         = Confirmed cases per 100k inhabitants by [[Counties of Ireland|county]]\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19)\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|Severe acute respiratory syndrome<br/>coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2)\n| source          = [[Bat]]s or possibly [[pangolin]]s<ref>{{cite journal |title=Identifying SARS-CoV-2 related coronaviruses in Malayan pangolins |journal=Nature |date=26 March 2020 |doi=10.1038/s41586-020-2169-0 |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-020-2169-0_reference.pdf |accessdate=27 March 2020|last1=Lam |first1=Tommy Tsan-Yuk |last2=Shum |first2=Marcus Ho-Hin |last3=Zhu |first3=Hua-Chen |last4=Tong |first4=Yi-Gang |last5=Ni |first5=Xue-Bing |last6=Liao |first6=Yun-Shi |last7=Wei |first7=Wei |last8=Cheung |first8=William Yiu-Man |last9=Li |first9=Wen-Juan |last10=Li |first10=Lian-Feng |last11=Leung |first11=Gabriel M. |last12=Holmes |first12=Edward C. |last13=Hu |first13=Yan-Ling |last14=Guan |first14=Yi |pmid=32218527 }}</ref><ref name=\"WHO report 28 February 2020\">{{cite web |url=https://www.who.int/docs/default-source/coronaviruse/who-china-joint-mission-on-covid-19-final-report.pdf |title=Report of the WHO-China Joint Mission on Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |date=16\u201324 February 2020 |access-date=8 March 2020 |author=WHO\u2013China Joint Mission |work=[[World Health Organization]]}}</ref><ref name=\"ia56U\">{{cite journal |title=Mystery deepens over animal source of coronavirus |journal=Nature |volume=579 |pages=18\u201319 |date=26 February 2020 |doi=10.1038/d41586-020-00548-w |pmid=32127703 |vauthors=Cyranoski D |issue=7797 |bibcode=2020Natur.579...18C|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n| location        = [[Republic of Ireland]]\n| first_case      = [[Dublin]]\n| arrival_date    = 29 February 2020<br/>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=02|day1=29|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}} ago)\n| origin          = [[Northern Italy]] (local)<br/>[[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]] (global)<br/>{{coord|30|35|14|N|114|17|17|E|type:adm2nd_region:CN-42}}\n| recovery_cases  = 9,233 <small>(as of 21 April 2020)</small><ref name=\"21 April\"/>\n| deaths          = 794 <small>(as of 23 April 2020)</small><ref name=\"23 April\"/>\n| confirmed_cases = 17,607 <small>(as of 23 April 2020)</small><ref name=\"23 April\"/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = [https://www.gov.ie/en/news/7e0924-latest-updates-on-covid-19-coronavirus/ Gov.ie - Latest updates on COVID-19 (Coronavirus)]\n| dates           = 8 March 2020\n}}\n\nConfirmation that the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ongoing 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] had spread to [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] came on 29 February 2020.<ref name=\"BBC News 1st Irish\">{{cite news |title=First case of coronavirus in Republic of Ireland |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51693259 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=29 February 2020 |accessdate=2020-03-02}}</ref> [[Tony Holohan]], the [[Chief Medical Officer (Ireland)|Chief Medical Officer]] for the [[Department of Health (Ireland)|Irish Department of Health]], announced its arrival.<ref name=\"BBC News 1st Irish\"/> By 20 March, around three weeks later, it was present in all [[Counties of Ireland|26 counties]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/health/coronavirus-cases-now-confirmed-in-every-county-in-ireland-1.4209389|title=Coronavirus cases now confirmed in every county in Ireland|first=Paul Cullen Health|last=Editor|website=[[The Irish Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thejournal.ie/breakdown-county-coronavirus-ireland-5054368-Mar2020/|title=Every single county in Ireland now has at least one coronavirus case - here's a breakdown of where the virus is|first=Garreth|last=MacNamee|website=TheJournal.ie}}</ref>\n\nThe pandemic's arrival affected many aspects of society, initially including the cancellation of [[Saint Patrick's Day|St Patrick's Day]] parades and all festivals.<ref name=\"Dublin Live Pat Parade canc\"/><ref name=\"Waterford Live Pat canc\"/><ref name=\"Echo parade canc\"/><ref name=\"BBC pat parades off\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51806551|title=Irish St Patrick's Day parades off over coronavirus|date=2020-03-09|publisher=[[BBC News]] |language=en-GB |access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> [[Taoiseach]] [[Leo Varadkar]] broke from a trip to [[Washington, D.C.]], where he was meeting with [[President of the United States]] [[Donald Trump]], to announce the closure of all schools, colleges, childcare and other public facilities until at least 29 March 2020.<ref name=\"Irish Times schools to shut\"/> These [[public health]] measures were subsequently expanded and extended until at least 19 April 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thejournal.ie/coronavirus-new-measures-5055686-Mar2020/|title=Taoiseach announces all non-essential shops to close, restrictions on gatherings of more than four people|last=Murray|first=Sean|website=[[TheJournal.ie]]|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Another extension carried the measures onwards until 5 May 2020 at the earliest.<ref name=\"extend\"/>\n\nOn 17 March, the [[Health Service Executive]] (HSE) launched a recruitment campaign, asking both healthcare professionals and non-healthcare professionals to \"be on call for Ireland\".<ref name=beon/> [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann|D\u00e1il]] and [[Seanad \u00c9ireann]] passed [[Health (Preservation and Protection and other Emergency Measures in the Public Interest) Act 2020|an emergency bill]]\u2014giving the state power to [[Detention (imprisonment)|detain]] people, restrict travel and keep people in their homes in order to help control the virus's spread\u2014with [[President of Ireland]] [[Michael D. Higgins]] signing it into law.<ref name=\"RTE Higgins signs emerg\"/>\n\n<!-- Please also update the stats in the Europe page also https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Europe#Ireland -->\nAs of 23 April, the [[Department of Health (Ireland)|Department of Health]] has confirmed 17,607 cases and 794 deaths.<ref name=\"23 April\">{{cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2020/0423/1134432-figures-covid-thursday-23-april/|title=Covid-19: 28 more deaths, 936 additional cases|publisher=[[RT\u00c9 News and Current Affairs]]|date=23 April 2020|accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\nThe surveillance of COVID-19 cases has been integrated into the existing national Computerised Infectious Disease Reporting (CIDR) system since COVID-19 was made a notifiable disease on 20 February 2020. CIDR is the information system used to manage the surveillance and control of infectious diseases in Ireland, both at regional and national level.<ref name=\"notifiable\">{{cite web|url=https://ndsc.newsweaver.ie/4otaa688p3/c2f2qexyyf210gkzp9yxn5?a=1&p=56582761&t=31302934|title=Minister for Health signs regulations to make COVID-19 a notifiable disease in Ireland|publisher=HSE [[Health Protection Surveillance Centre]] |date=1 March 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> Daily epidemiological reports on COVID-19 are prepared by the [[Health Protection Surveillance Centre]] for the [[National Public Health Emergency Team]] (NPHET).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.ie/en/news/7e0924-latest-updates-on-covid-19-coronavirus/|title=Latest updates on COVID-19 (Coronavirus)|publisher=[[Department of Health]] |date=10 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n{{Side box\n |metadata=No<!--The value 'No' apparently makes the box display on the mobile site-->\n | position = left<!--To align with the other graphs on the page.-->\n | above = '''Confirmed COVID-19 Cases'''\n|abovestyle=text-align:center|text={{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=2\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=600\n|colors=#FF4500,#7a7677,#f1f527,lightblue\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-60\n|x=29 Feb,1 Mar,2 Mar,3 Mar,4 Mar,5 Mar,6 Mar,7 Mar,8 Mar,9 Mar,10 Mar,11 Mar,12 Mar,13 Mar,14 Mar,15 Mar,16 Mar,17 Mar,18 Mar, 19 Mar, 20 Mar,21 Mar,22 Mar,23 Mar,24 Mar,25 Mar,26 Mar,27 Mar,28 Mar,29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar,1 Apr,2 Apr,3 Apr,4 Apr,5 Apr,6 Apr,7 Apr,8 Apr,9 Apr,10 Apr,11 Apr,12 Apr,13 Apr,14 Apr,15 Apr, 16 Apr,17 Apr,18 Apr,19 Apr,20 Apr,21 Apr,22 Apr,23 Apr\n|yAxisTitle=Cases\n|y1Title=Total confirmed cases\n|y1=1,1,1,2,6,13,18,19,21,24,34,43,70,90,129,169,223,292,366,557,683,785,906,1125,1329,1564,1819,2121,2415,2615,2910,3235,3447,3849,4273,4604,4994,5364,5709,6074,6574,8089,8928,9655,10647,11479,12547,13271,13980,14758,15251,15652,16040,16671,17607\n|y2=,,,,,,,,,,,1,1,1,2,2,2,2,2,3,3,3,4,6,7,9,19,22,36,46,54,71,85,98,120,137,158,174,210,235,263,288,320,334,365,406,444,486,530,571,610,687,730,769,794\n|y3=,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,59,84,114,147,159,208,247,283,321,375,445,506,578,674,752,841,948,1084,1163,1263,1388,1568,1765,1949,2141,2312,2489,2707,2872,3090,3347,3578,3788,4009,4180,4393,4545\n|y4=,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,77,,,,,9233,,9233\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n{{legend|#FF4500|Total Confirmed Cases.\n{{legend|#f1f527|Total Healthcare Worker Confirmed Cases.\n{{legend|lightblue|Total Recoveries.\n{{legend|#7a7677|Total Deaths.\n}}}}}}\n}}}}\n\n{{Side box\n |metadata=No<!--The value 'No' apparently makes the box display on the mobile si